{"term":"1969","caseName":"United States v. Sisson","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1969/305","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 20, 1970","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger1/oral_argument_audio/14952","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will take Number 305, United States against Sisson.","start":0,"stop":22.269,"duration":22.27},{"text":"Mr. Solicitor General.","start":22.269,"stop":25.178,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":25.178,"stop":31.271,"duration":6.09},{"text":"This too is a draft case raising two new unrelated and difficult problems.","start":31.271,"stop":42.433,"duration":11.16},{"text":"In a third aspect it's like the Welsh case which has just been argued.","start":42.433,"stop":48.758,"duration":6.33},{"text":"And for my argument on the question relating to religious training and belief, I rely on the argument in the case just concluded.","start":48.758,"stop":62.838,"duration":14.08},{"text":"The defendant here was indicted for failing to report for induction.","start":62.838,"stop":68.823,"duration":5.98},{"text":"There was a trial before jury at which the defendant testified.","start":68.823,"stop":75.919,"duration":7.1},{"text":"The jury returned a verdict of guilty.","start":75.919,"stop":80.146,"duration":4.23},{"text":"The defendant then made a motion in arrest of judgment.","start":80.146,"stop":85.236,"duration":5.09},{"text":"In his motion, the defendant said that he could not participate in the Vietnam War without doing violence to the dictates of his conscience.","start":85.236,"stop":97.894,"duration":12.66},{"text":"And he further stated that, he cannot qualify as a conscientious objector within the meaning of the Military Selective Service Act of 1967 because he is not a pacifist.","start":97.894,"stop":113.119,"duration":15.22},{"text":"And in any event, his convictions that the Vietnam War is illegal, immoral, and unjust are not based on religious training and belief.","start":113.119,"stop":127.031,"duration":13.91},{"text":"The District Court granted the motion in arrest of judgment and so doing it referred to facts which had appeared at the trial and noted that particularly the defendants own testimony.","start":127.031,"stop":144.228,"duration":17.2},{"text":"And noted that “in substance the case arises upon an agreed statement of facts,” that appears on page 250 of the appendix.","start":144.228,"stop":155.898,"duration":11.67},{"text":"I can state that none of the facts is controvert.","start":155.898,"stop":161.36,"duration":5.46},{"text":"We do not dispute that the appellee was sincerely and conscientiously opposed to the Vietnam conflict based on his moral convictions, educational training, extensive reading both about Vietnam, and about such things as the UN Charter and the Nuremberg Trial.","start":161.36,"stop":185.274,"duration":23.91},{"text":"As I have indicated, his claim is selective not against war in any form as the phrase is in the statute.","start":185.274,"stop":195.415,"duration":10.14},{"text":"And he expressly asserts that it is not based on religious training and belief.","start":195.415,"stop":203.049,"duration":7.63},{"text":"In this situation, the District Court held that the appellee had a valid claim to be constitutionally exempted from combat in the Vietnam type of situation.","start":203.049,"stop":216.155,"duration":13.11}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think this is a motion in arrest of judgment or motion for an acquittal?","start":216.155,"stop":223.988,"duration":7.83}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a subject to which I am about to address my argument.","start":223.988,"stop":227.843,"duration":3.85},{"text":"It is the -- I was trying to give the setting.","start":227.843,"stop":231.505,"duration":3.66},{"text":"The first half of my argument is devoted to jurisdiction and the second half to selective conscientious objection.","start":231.505,"stop":239.923,"duration":8.42},{"text":"The Court concluded that the Military Service Act violated the free exercise in Due Process Clauses.","start":239.923,"stop":247.36,"duration":7.44},{"text":"It held in the alternative of Section 6 (j) the exemption provision violated the Establishment Clause and that it unreasonably discriminated between religious and non-religious conscientious objection.","start":247.36,"stop":262.053,"duration":14.69},{"text":"From this decision, the United States took this appeal purporting to act under the Second Clause of the Criminal Appeal Act of 1907.","start":262.053,"stop":273.253,"duration":11.2},{"text":"Now, found in Title 18 of the United States Code Section 3731, the relevant passages from which are set out on page 13 of the Government's brief.","start":273.253,"stop":285.206,"duration":11.95},{"text":"And now, I will turn to the jurisdictional question which in my mind is a very close question.","start":285.206,"stop":293.091,"duration":7.88},{"text":"We contend that there is jurisdiction but arguments can be made both ways.","start":293.091,"stop":300.898,"duration":7.81},{"text":"There's no doubt that there was a trial here and if there had been a verdict of not guilty even a directive verdict of not guilty.","start":300.898,"stop":311.328,"duration":10.43},{"text":"There could be no appeal no matter what error of law was made by the trial court.","start":311.328,"stop":318.147,"duration":6.82},{"text":"An illustration of that is found in the case decided just last month of United States against Bond which is set out in appendix to one of the briefs filed by amici curiae, the one by the Los Angeles selective service law panel.","start":318.147,"stop":339.561,"duration":21.41},{"text":"In the Bond case, Judge Weigel directed the verdict for the defendant, who was a selective conscientious objector based on religious training and belief.","start":339.561,"stop":350.743,"duration":11.18},{"text":"We think that Judge Weigel was wrong as the matter of law but there's nothing we can do about it and we have of course taken no appeal.","start":350.743,"stop":361.195,"duration":10.45},{"text":"The difference is that here there was a verdict of guilty followed by a motion and arrest of judgment which was granted.","start":361.195,"stop":370.579,"duration":9.38},{"text":"Now, if Judge Wyzanski had entered an order saying, having examined the record I find that there was no sufficient evidence to submit to the jury, and the case should not have been allowed to go to the jury and accordingly, I direct to the judgment of acquittal be entered.","start":370.579,"stop":388.191,"duration":17.61},{"text":"I think we would be so close to the situation in the Bond case that we couldn't talked about it.","start":388.191,"stop":394.301,"duration":6.11},{"text":"And it is easy I think to say that, what Judge Wyzanski did is not different in substance from that and that summarizes the difficulty of our position on the jurisdiction.","start":394.301,"stop":408.625,"duration":14.32}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's one important difference though in that the verdict and judgments stands now, does it not?","start":408.625,"stop":416.87,"duration":8.25},{"text":"In your first illustration a judgment notwithstanding the verdict that there would be no verdict any longer but the verdict still stands here, does it not?","start":416.87,"stop":428.08,"duration":11.21}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure Mr. Justice.","start":428.08,"stop":430.268,"duration":2.19},{"text":"The judge --","start":430.268,"stop":430.601,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what --","start":430.601,"stop":431.33,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"The judge has decided that there was no basis in law for the verdict.","start":431.33,"stop":435.674,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what was -- what was the language of his order was?","start":435.674,"stop":440.765,"duration":5.09}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not in the appendix.","start":440.765,"stop":443.759,"duration":2.99},{"text":"I can't tell you the language.","start":443.759,"stop":445.948,"duration":2.19},{"text":"The opinion is here but the actual judgment is not here.","start":445.948,"stop":449.658,"duration":3.71},{"text":"I discovered to my surprise last night, page 264, enter forthwith this decision in this Court's order granting defendant systems, motion and arrest of judgment.","start":449.658,"stop":462.277,"duration":12.62},{"text":"And there --","start":462.277,"stop":462.908,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when you -- this is the language I had in mind.","start":462.908,"stop":466.614,"duration":3.71},{"text":"It's in arrest of judgment.","start":466.614,"stop":467.958,"duration":1.34},{"text":"He is acknowledging the existence of the judgment which presupposes that it rests and turn upon a verdict and he hasn't done -- he hasn't expressed or articulated any idea of setting aside that verdict nor does he vacate the judgment he said, he arrests --","start":467.958,"stop":487.645,"duration":19.69}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"There has been no judgment.","start":487.645,"stop":489.785,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the language you read again?","start":489.785,"stop":492.661,"duration":2.88},{"text":"Excuse me, I'm looking for it in the appendix but I don't find it precise --","start":492.661,"stop":499.561,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"250 -- 250 is the only place that I can find it, enter forthwith this decision and this Court's order, granting defendant Sisson's motion in arrest of judgment.","start":499.561,"stop":511.199,"duration":11.64},{"text":"Now that is in arrest of judgment, there had not previously been any judgment and a motion in arrest of judgment, not in arrest of the execution of judgment but in arrest of entering judgment as I interpret it.","start":511.199,"stop":525.506,"duration":14.31},{"text":"I -- if you're --","start":525.506,"stop":526.798,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that puzzles me a little bit.","start":526.798,"stop":529.01,"duration":2.21},{"text":"I did not know whether he -- from this language was arresting a judgment, the execution of a judgment entered, or arresting the entry of the judgment based on the verdict.","start":529.01,"stop":539.319,"duration":10.31},{"text":"But in either case the verdict stands, does it not?","start":539.319,"stop":542.455,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"The verdict is in a historical fact, no doubt about that.","start":542.455,"stop":544.415,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- its --","start":544.415,"stop":547.444,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Its legal effect has been undermined by the District Judge's decision.","start":547.444,"stop":552.641,"duration":5.2},{"text":"He had decided that it is not a proper basis to found a judgment of the Court of conviction.","start":552.641,"stop":559.639,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But when a sophisticated, highly experienced District Judge makes the choice between a judgments entering judgment notwithstanding a verdict in this posture, and the action which he did take.","start":559.639,"stop":575.063,"duration":15.42},{"text":"Does that suggest anything to -- should that suggest anything to us?","start":575.063,"stop":578.709,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"It may have suggests -- may suggest that he was trying to preserve a situation which would make it possible for us to appeal to this Court.","start":578.709,"stop":587.833,"duration":9.12}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Not a -- that's among other things, one of the incidental factors which occurred to me but in so doing, he has left a verdict extent without on its face --","start":587.833,"stop":604.575,"duration":16.74}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's --","start":604.575,"stop":605.852,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on its face entered.","start":605.852,"stop":606.687,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I hate to be arguing against myself here Mr. Chief Justice, but he has left the verdict stand but he's pulled all the foundation out from under so, its floats in space I guess.","start":606.687,"stop":617.297,"duration":10.61},{"text":"It is no longer a basis for entering a judgment of conviction.","start":617.297,"stop":622.71,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask the Mr. Solicitor General.","start":622.71,"stop":625.827,"duration":3.12},{"text":"This is an appeal isn't it, a direct appeal?","start":625.827,"stop":629.214,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice.","start":629.214,"stop":630.952,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It must be from the judgment, must have not?","start":630.952,"stop":634.617,"duration":3.66},{"text":"We -- I thought you said --","start":634.617,"stop":635.51,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"It is from -- it is from a judgment or order in arrest of judgment which is the express --","start":635.51,"stop":641.397,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well my point is, I gather we've often said that we don't review opinions here we review judgments.","start":641.397,"stop":649.769,"duration":8.37}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Mr. Justice.","start":649.769,"stop":650.812,"duration":1.04},{"text":"You don't review opinions but the criminal --","start":650.812,"stop":652.432,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute says, from a decision, does it?","start":652.432,"stop":654.707,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"The Criminal Appeals Act provides that there is an appeal to this Court from a decision arresting a judgment of conviction.","start":654.707,"stop":665.163,"duration":10.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I know a decision.","start":665.163,"stop":666.083,"duration":0.92},{"text":"What's a decision -- what forms of decision take to purposes of appeal?","start":666.083,"stop":671.444,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"From a decision arresting a judgment of conviction for insufficient --","start":671.444,"stop":674.85,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I ask again.","start":674.85,"stop":675.857,"duration":1.01},{"text":"I ask again, what form does a decision take?","start":675.857,"stop":678.824,"duration":2.97},{"text":"Do we have another jurisdictional question here?","start":678.824,"stop":680.785,"duration":1.96},{"text":"Will we have any appeal here at all?","start":680.785,"stop":682.117,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so, Mr. Justice.","start":682.117,"stop":683.917,"duration":1.8},{"text":"I think the decision is --","start":683.917,"stop":685.993,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The opinion?","start":685.993,"stop":686.804,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the opinion and the final order at the end, beginning on page 248 and concluding on page 264 of the appendix.","start":686.804,"stop":698.177,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Any rate that's the, not only the only order there is but that's the order which protects system and from which the Government is.","start":698.177,"stop":707.526,"duration":9.35},{"text":"And there can be no doubt that while that stands Sisson completely protected and that is the order from which the Government is seeking to give.","start":707.526,"stop":717.184,"duration":9.66}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But General, how do we -- aren't we further confused by the fact that it was a motion towards the indictment at the beginning of it, which he denied?","start":717.184,"stop":727.226,"duration":10.04}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"There was a motion too Mr. Justice --","start":727.226,"stop":728.788,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"To quash the indictment?","start":728.788,"stop":730.492,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":730.492,"stop":730.763,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Dismissing the --","start":730.763,"stop":731.499,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Which was -- which was denied --","start":731.499,"stop":732.988,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Was denied.","start":732.988,"stop":734.794,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"There were several motions before a trial, all of which were --","start":734.794,"stop":737.856,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Then one of them was that and yet, after the trial then he dismisses it.","start":737.856,"stop":741.342,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"In this motion, the arrest of judgment to some extent the grounds are the same as those which were presented in motions made before the trial.","start":741.342,"stop":752.132,"duration":10.79},{"text":"Now in this case, if the motion had been granted on the fact that the statute was unconstitutional on its face, there would I think would be no doubt that this Court would have jurisdiction of the appeal.","start":752.132,"stop":765.838,"duration":13.71},{"text":"But in fact, the motion was granted on the ground that in the later the facts appearing at the trial, the statute is unconstitutional as applied to this particular defendant.","start":765.838,"stop":778.644,"duration":12.81},{"text":"If those facts had appeared in and agreed statement of fact, this Court's decision in United States against Halseth in 342 U.S. would support the jurisdiction.","start":778.644,"stop":794.127,"duration":15.48},{"text":"Here the facts appeared in testimony but are accepted by the Government so, that there is a basis for the District Court's statement that the case in substance arises upon an aggrieved statement of facts.","start":794.127,"stop":810.305,"duration":16.18},{"text":"We never formally agreed to them but we don't dispute them.","start":810.305,"stop":815.673,"duration":5.37}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How can you dispute them he's going to lose this case?","start":815.673,"stop":821.868,"duration":6.2},{"text":"You need to agree to him in order to give him the right to arrest of the judgment?","start":821.868,"stop":828.108,"duration":6.24}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we would lose our right to appeal if we --","start":828.108,"stop":831.662,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":831.662,"stop":832.055,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"-- dispute them, I agree and we don't.","start":832.055,"stop":835.114,"duration":3.06},{"text":"We don't.","start":835.114,"stop":837.018,"duration":1.9},{"text":"In this situation, we have concluded not without difficulty that to construe the Criminal Appeals Act as precluding appeal of the decision below would unwarrantedly exalt form over substance.","start":837.018,"stop":853.555,"duration":16.54},{"text":"There is no genuine difference between this case and one in which the nature of the appellees conscientious objection would be set forth in the indictment itself or formerly stipulated to on a motion to dismiss.","start":853.555,"stop":872.221,"duration":18.67},{"text":"We think too that the decision below is one on the construction of Section 12 (a) of the Selective Service Act.","start":872.221,"stop":881.217,"duration":9},{"text":"Less clearly, we think that the Court's decision with respect to Section 6 (j) comes within the Criminal Appeals Act.","start":881.217,"stop":890.214,"duration":9},{"text":"You have to go through 6 (j) to get to 12 (a) to -- in order to make it a construction of the statute.","start":890.214,"stop":899.773,"duration":9.56},{"text":"Now, there are two other Clauses of the Criminal Appeals Act, one, relating to a judgment setting aside or dismissing any indictment or information; and the other relating to a -- the sustaining of a motion in bar and its order postponing the question of jurisdiction in this case.","start":899.773,"stop":920.58,"duration":20.81},{"text":"The Court requested the parties to direct their attention to this other provisions and we‘ve done so at some length in our brief.","start":920.58,"stop":928.592,"duration":8.01},{"text":"I may say that there are few problems which reoccur so frequently or present such extreme technical difficulty in the Solicitor General's office than the proper construction of the Criminal Appeals Act, you had the Jorn case last week which was a problem.","start":928.592,"stop":948.98,"duration":20.39},{"text":"There are also other provisions --","start":948.98,"stop":950.327,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Still is?","start":950.327,"stop":950.709,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the Act relating the one you can appeal the Courts of Appeals.","start":950.709,"stop":954.359,"duration":3.65},{"text":"We find that if we appeal to a Court of Appeals, they transfer to the Supreme Court.","start":954.359,"stop":960.04,"duration":5.68},{"text":"So far, we haven't had much problem with the Supreme Court transferring them back to the Court of Appeals but the clauses are --","start":960.04,"stop":968.369,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But may I ask Mr. Solicitor General, do you see any similarity in the problem here to that in Jorn?","start":968.369,"stop":976.229,"duration":7.86}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Mr. Justice.","start":976.229,"stop":977.236,"duration":1.01},{"text":"I don't believe I do.","start":977.236,"stop":980.348,"duration":3.11},{"text":"In Jorn, as far as the second trial is concerned, the defendant had not been put in jeopardy and the only issue is whether the jeopardy of the first trial is wiped out or not so as to make the appeal available.","start":980.348,"stop":999.417,"duration":19.07},{"text":"Here --","start":999.417,"stop":999.464,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, strictly speaking and that was only a second stage not a second trial but a second stage on the same proceeding in Jorn.","start":999.464,"stop":1006.864,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it was a second trial under the same indictment.","start":1006.864,"stop":1010.831,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Under an amended information?","start":1010.831,"stop":1013.146,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"An information, yes Your Honor.","start":1013.146,"stop":1014.746,"duration":1.6},{"text":"I don't recall whether the amendment was made following the first trial or during trial.","start":1014.746,"stop":1019.262,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"After the first stage of the proceeding in that was met.","start":1019.262,"stop":1021.126,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1021.126,"stop":1023.319,"duration":2.19},{"text":"Now the clause relating the motions in bar, it seems to us rather obviously inapplicable since by its terms, it's available only when the defendant has not been put in jeopardy.","start":1023.319,"stop":1038.077,"duration":14.76},{"text":"Here, the appellee has clearly been put in jeopardy.","start":1038.077,"stop":1041.89,"duration":3.81},{"text":"Not only was the jury empanelled but a verdict was rendered against him.","start":1041.89,"stop":1046.7,"duration":4.81},{"text":"Moreover, the legislative history which is set out at some length in our brief shows great concern on the part of responsible Senators that this new and for its time rather bold statute, should not transgress any constitutional limits, particularly with respect to double jeopardy.","start":1046.7,"stop":1067.267,"duration":20.57},{"text":"I just do not see how we can get any helped from the motion in the bar clause.","start":1067.267,"stop":1074.154,"duration":6.89},{"text":"And finally, there is the clause relating to setting aside or dismissing any indictment or information.","start":1074.154,"stop":1083.424,"duration":9.27},{"text":"There is no verbal limitation there with respect to jeopardy and a literal reading of the provision might lead to the conclusion that it provides a basis for jurisdiction here.","start":1083.424,"stop":1095.397,"duration":11.97},{"text":"In its original form, this clause related to decisions on demur and such decisions would be rendered before or nearly this before jeopardy.","start":1095.397,"stop":1108.423,"duration":13.03},{"text":"Seven months following the enactment of the statute, this Court indicated that the provision applied and I quote “To judgments rendered before the moment of jeopardy is reach,” and that's United States against Macdonald in 207 U.S.","start":1108.423,"stop":1126.948,"duration":18.53},{"text":"And this has been the consistent construction of the provision by the Department of Justice over a period of more than 60 years.","start":1126.948,"stop":1136.33,"duration":9.38},{"text":"A little more than 20 years ago, a case called Zisblatt came to this Court and Solicitor General Perlman, actually had came through the Court of Appeals and was certified to this Court.","start":1136.33,"stop":1149.734,"duration":13.4},{"text":"Solicitor General Perlman moved that the appeal to be dismissed because there jeopardy had attached.","start":1149.734,"stop":1156.671,"duration":6.94},{"text":"We have searched through the files to try to find some greater statement of the reasons but have not found that.","start":1156.671,"stop":1169.699,"duration":13.03},{"text":"There is no doubt I believe that it was the expectation of the legislators while the bill was going through Congress.","start":1169.699,"stop":1178.476,"duration":8.78},{"text":"That the rulings to which the bill related would occur before a jury was sworn except for decision rendered on a motion and arrest of judgment.","start":1178.476,"stop":1190.536,"duration":12.06},{"text":"We're not prepared to dispute this contemporaneous understanding and the interpretation of the Act at which has obtained since 1907.","start":1190.536,"stop":1202.25,"duration":11.71},{"text":"It's true that the statute has been amended particularly when it was codified in 1908 -- in 1948 but the reviser's note at that time makes it plain that the changes then made were editorial only and were not intended to order the scope of review.","start":1202.25,"stop":1222.975,"duration":20.72},{"text":"Over the years, the Department of Justice has repeatedly sought to get the statute change, I might say modernized, and such an effort is pending now.","start":1222.975,"stop":1234.718,"duration":11.74},{"text":"But there have been no changes and the law today would be seemed to be essentially the same as it enacted in 1907.","start":1234.718,"stop":1242.278,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible), did you say that your -- is there objection to it in Congress or just admission of --","start":1242.278,"stop":1251.052,"duration":8.77}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Mr. Justice.","start":1251.052,"stop":1252.399,"duration":1.35},{"text":"It's just hard to get things through Congress even when there is no objection.","start":1252.399,"stop":1258.146,"duration":5.75},{"text":"Congressman McCulloch, the raking minority member of the House Judiciary Committee, is interested in this now and we hopes that he will make some progress not only on this, but on the statute dealing with the direct appeals and Interstate Commerce Commission cases and from three judge courts.","start":1258.146,"stop":1279.543,"duration":21.4},{"text":"And I can only say that where the statute passed it would greatly simplify the worked of the Solicitor General's office.","start":1279.543,"stop":1286.645,"duration":7.1}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"How about us?","start":1286.645,"stop":1288.086,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"How about?","start":1288.086,"stop":1289.113,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Would it simplify our tasks too?","start":1289.113,"stop":1294.645,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"You might have more petitions to certiorari to examine or to review at Courts of Appeals.","start":1294.645,"stop":1299.976,"duration":5.33},{"text":"I don't know whether it would or not because the existing effect is that a great many cases are not appealed at all that ought to be appealed.","start":1299.976,"stop":1309.763,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Simply because we feel that we cannot appropriately bring such a case to this Court and we would take it to a Court of Appeals.","start":1309.763,"stop":1317.476,"duration":7.71},{"text":"And would very likely abide by the decision of the Court of Appeals and such I think Jorn is a clear example.","start":1317.476,"stop":1325.635,"duration":8.16},{"text":"I -- we were sorry to bring that case here there is no place else we could go.","start":1325.635,"stop":1329.476,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask Mr. Solicitor is Justice Sparksman --","start":1329.476,"stop":1332.507,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice.","start":1332.507,"stop":1333.561,"duration":1.05},{"text":"Yes.","start":1333.561,"stop":1334.097,"duration":0.54},{"text":"It says a full support of the department but so it did over the past five or six years there has been an active effort to get it done.","start":1334.097,"stop":1346.601,"duration":12.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any documentation (Inaudible), what I mean are they significant to the committee?","start":1346.601,"stop":1355.097,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe it's gotten to a committee.","start":1355.097,"stop":1358.381,"duration":3.28},{"text":"We did refer to the fact in our brief in this case that we had efforts pending but I don't know whether anything is cited now or not.","start":1358.381,"stop":1379.748,"duration":21.37},{"text":"No, I don't have any.","start":1379.748,"stop":1381.239,"duration":1.49},{"text":"I -- I'm quite sure that there is no committee report.","start":1381.239,"stop":1383.685,"duration":2.45},{"text":"I suspect that the only thing that is available is the usual letter from the Deputy Attorney General which ordinarily is not a public document.","start":1383.685,"stop":1396.107,"duration":12.42},{"text":"On this basis, our position is that the only basis for jurisdiction here is the arresting a judgment clause even that's a little shaky as I tried to indicate.","start":1396.107,"stop":1415.21,"duration":19.1},{"text":"But for the reasons I've given earlier, our submission is that that provision can appropriately be construed to support this Court's jurisdiction of the appeal.","start":1415.21,"stop":1427.905,"duration":12.69},{"text":"And now, I turn to the merits in the Sisson case assuming that I'm validly here.","start":1427.905,"stop":1438.298,"duration":10.39},{"text":"As I have already indicated, it involves nonreligious, selective objector.","start":1438.298,"stop":1449.337,"duration":11.04},{"text":"Judge Wyzanski held the indictment invalid on both grounds religious and selective.","start":1449.337,"stop":1456.74,"duration":7.4},{"text":"We think he was wrong on both grounds.","start":1456.74,"stop":1461.082,"duration":4.34},{"text":"If he was wrong on the selective objection ground, he need not have considered the nonreligious character of the objection.","start":1461.082,"stop":1470.539,"duration":9.46},{"text":"As I've already indicated, we rely on the argument in the Welsh case so, far as the question of the reference to religious training and belief in the statute is concerned.","start":1470.539,"stop":1483.665,"duration":13.13},{"text":"And that leaves for consideration here, the question of selective conscientious objection.","start":1483.665,"stop":1492.999,"duration":9.33},{"text":"That is the question of the validity of the provision which Congress has included in the statute that exemption will be allowed when the registrant and I quote from Section 6 (j), “His conscientiously opposed to participation in war in any form.”","start":1492.999,"stop":1515.257,"duration":22.26},{"text":"There's no suggestion that the appellee comes within the terms of that statute.","start":1515.257,"stop":1519.999,"duration":4.74},{"text":"We have no possible question of statutory construction here with respect to that.","start":1519.999,"stop":1526.357,"duration":6.36},{"text":"His objection is to the Vietnam War.","start":1526.357,"stop":1529.912,"duration":3.56},{"text":"He asserts that he is not a pacifist, thus, unless the statute is in some way invalid.","start":1529.912,"stop":1537.629,"duration":7.72},{"text":"He is not entitled to an exemption quite without regard to whether his objection is based on religious training and belief.","start":1537.629,"stop":1546.364,"duration":8.74},{"text":"And it was for that reason that I allocated the religious argument to the Welsh case and the selective argument back to this case.","start":1546.364,"stop":1556.862,"duration":10.5},{"text":"It may well be noted in the first place that the appellee has not been indicted for failure to obey and order to go to Vietnam.","start":1556.862,"stop":1567.941,"duration":11.08},{"text":"He is being prosecuted for failure to submit to induction in the Armed Forces.","start":1567.941,"stop":1574.493,"duration":6.55},{"text":"Thus, the Court undertook to excuse a deliberate violation of the law on the basis of events which may or may not occur in the future.","start":1574.493,"stop":1587.628,"duration":13.13},{"text":"Assuming that the question is reached, we think that the District Court look far beyond the limits of the proper exercise of judicial power in undertaking decide on the basis of its balancing of the considerations, whether an individual's conscientious objection to a particular war, gave him a constitutional right to disobey an Act of Congress.","start":1587.628,"stop":1618.717,"duration":31.09},{"text":"In our view, the constitutional grant of power to Congress, to raise and maintain armies is not properly subject to the balancing approach applied in the instant case.","start":1618.717,"stop":1633.402,"duration":14.68},{"text":"It is not a power to raise and maintain armies when in the view of a Court it seems that on a whole the arguments in favor of it outweigh the particular objections which could be raised by an individual oppose to it.","start":1633.402,"stop":1650.746,"duration":17.34},{"text":"The weighing of considerations, the determination of necessity, of necessity and details is for Congress and not the courts.","start":1650.746,"stop":1662.876,"duration":12.13},{"text":"Congress must of course act constitutionally, but it is not the problems of the courts to decide whether a particular law or a particular foreign policy is good or bad or whether there is or is not any need for specified numbers of man in a particular place at a certain time.","start":1662.876,"stop":1685.721,"duration":22.85},{"text":"Judges are not the person's charge with the responsibility for determining the national need for military manpower.","start":1685.721,"stop":1695.216,"duration":9.49},{"text":"So far as the selective conscientious objector is concerned, Congress has made no discrimination between religious and nonreligious motivations.","start":1695.216,"stop":1707.699,"duration":12.48},{"text":"Thus, the Establishment Clause has no bearing on the issues here involved.","start":1707.699,"stop":1714.766,"duration":7.07},{"text":"Even in its broadest conceivable construction nor can this case properly be brought within the Free Exercise Clause.","start":1714.766,"stop":1724.45,"duration":9.68},{"text":"Religious freedom does not require that religious scruples be recognized as justifying disobedience to a valid law.","start":1724.45,"stop":1734.765,"duration":10.32},{"text":"This Court had so said quite clearly in Hamilton against the Regents in 293 U.S. where they quoted from the opinion in United States against Macintosh, this is on pages 44 and 45 of our brief, and then there is at the bottom of page 45, a quotation from an opinion of Judge Augustus Hand who I think, I may appropriately say is perhaps my favorite federal judge.","start":1734.765,"stop":1774.439,"duration":39.67},{"text":"There is a distinction between a course of reasoning resulting in a conviction under particular war is inexpedient or disastrous and conscientious objection to participation in any war under any circumstances.","start":1774.439,"stop":1790.011,"duration":15.57},{"text":"The latter not the former may be the basis of exemption under the Act and it surely never occurred to Judge Hand that there was any legal question lying behind that statement.","start":1790.011,"stop":1802.907,"duration":12.9},{"text":"The former is usually a political objection.","start":1802.907,"stop":1806.471,"duration":3.56},{"text":"While the latter we think may justly be regarded as a response of the individual to an inward matter.","start":1806.471,"stop":1813.646,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Call it, conscience are gone, that is for many persons at the present time the equivalent of what has always been thought a religious impulse.","start":1813.646,"stop":1826.095,"duration":12.45},{"text":"Only if the Free Exercise Clause is broadened to encompass a general right of conscience would that provision be useful to the appellee.","start":1826.095,"stop":1839.833,"duration":13.74},{"text":"And there are extensive arguments in the briefs of amici curiae to the effect that the First Amendment does command a general right of conscience.","start":1839.833,"stop":1855.93,"duration":16.1},{"text":"That goes beyond but the amendment says, beyond anything that this Court has ever decided and it seems to me would be a wholly unwarranted and unjustified.","start":1855.93,"stop":1870.798,"duration":14.87},{"text":"If that provision was given such sweeping scope, it would have necessity extend beyond the Selective Service Act to other areas.","start":1870.798,"stop":1882.594,"duration":11.8},{"text":"Such as the payments of taxes or to people have conscientious scruples against the racial equality.","start":1882.594,"stop":1891.201,"duration":8.61},{"text":"And I have no doubt that there are such people whose conscience seems perfectly clear on that matter unless the Fourteenth Amendment was held to have pro tanto repeal the First Amendment which seems a curious reversal of the operation of those provisions.","start":1891.201,"stop":1913.553,"duration":22.35},{"text":"Such a construction of the First Amendment is without precedent.","start":1913.553,"stop":1918.369,"duration":4.82},{"text":"It would be wholly destructive of the orderly functioning of Government.","start":1918.369,"stop":1923.821,"duration":5.45},{"text":"And it would undermine the essential integrity of the democratic process.","start":1923.821,"stop":1929.269,"duration":5.45},{"text":"It is true of course, that we are a constitutional government.","start":1929.269,"stop":1933.725,"duration":4.46},{"text":"But we are also a government one of whose great principals is majority rule.","start":1933.725,"stop":1939.762,"duration":6.04},{"text":"The acts -- asked by the elective representatives of the people are the law.","start":1939.762,"stop":1946.031,"duration":6.27},{"text":"They are subject to the Constitution but the elective representatives of the people make the political decisions.","start":1946.031,"stop":1953.552,"duration":7.52}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Solicitor General, may I ask you this?","start":1953.552,"stop":1957.093,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Would you see any difference in the posture of the basic claims of this appellant?","start":1957.093,"stop":1964.534,"duration":7.44},{"text":"And that of a taxpayer who refuse to pay any taxes so long as the -- some of the taxes were being used to maintain a war that he objected to on the same grounds?","start":1964.534,"stop":1976.09,"duration":11.56}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no Mr. Justice.","start":1976.09,"stop":1977.143,"duration":1.05},{"text":"That is essentially the argument I would just trying to make that pressing -- pressing the First Amendment to establish a constitutional right of free conscience could not be limited to the Selective Service Act.","start":1977.143,"stop":1992.331,"duration":15.19},{"text":"It could apply to all across the board anything which a person sincerely, conscientiously objects to.","start":1992.331,"stop":2001.104,"duration":8.77},{"text":"He would be protected in his objection by the Constitution including as far as I can see that of course would be another issue which would have to argue before this Court decided and the Court might find some way to make a distinction, but I can't make the distinction now.","start":2001.104,"stop":2016.263,"duration":15.16},{"text":"It seems to me, that it would follow that particularly since Flast and Gordon that -- not only since Flast and Gordon, Flast and Cohen but if the premise is the Constitution protects people in conscientious nonreligious objections.","start":2016.263,"stop":2038.846,"duration":22.58},{"text":"Then it seems to me, that it would follow that a citizen could refuse to pay either any taxes or conceivably some kind of a pro rata allocation of his taxes, insofar as they or perhaps, we would have to set up separate funds and this taxes could go into a fund which couldn't be used for defense purposes and other people's taxes would go into the defense fund.","start":2038.846,"stop":2064.328,"duration":25.48},{"text":"It seems to me that pressing the general language of the First Amendment that far would be pushing it to a dryly logical extreme.","start":2064.328,"stop":2078.105,"duration":13.78},{"text":"And finally, we contend that the provision made by Congress does not violate the Fifth Amendment.","start":2078.105,"stop":2086.428,"duration":8.32},{"text":"Congress could rationally distinguish between persons oppose to war in any form and those whose objections extend only to a particular war or situation.","start":2086.428,"stop":2100.626,"duration":14.2},{"text":"This is not a question of sincerity or depth of conviction but opposition to a particular war necessarily involved a practical and essentially political judgment.","start":2100.626,"stop":2116.587,"duration":15.96},{"text":"It represents the individual's personal conclusion that the policy adopted by the duly elected representatives of the Government is wrong at a certain time in relation to a particular area of operations.","start":2116.587,"stop":2134.205,"duration":17.62},{"text":"Those who oppose participation in combat in any form do not make the same type of immediate political judgment.","start":2134.205,"stop":2145.534,"duration":11.33},{"text":"Congress may validly conclude that there is a qualitative difference between persons who is beliefs caused them to opposed participation in all wars.","start":2145.534,"stop":2158.829,"duration":13.3},{"text":"And those who wish to reserved the right to choose the wars in which they will fight.","start":2158.829,"stop":2167.143,"duration":8.31},{"text":"Except for the court below and Judge Weigel and the District Court in California to which I've made reference.","start":2167.143,"stop":2177.007,"duration":9.86},{"text":"All of the courts which have considered the matter have held that Congress may validly draw a distinction between those who oppose all wars and those whose objection is only to a particular war.","start":2177.007,"stop":2192.044,"duration":15.04},{"text":"The District Court took the position that the magnitude of an individual's conscientious objection is not presumably lessened because his beliefs relate to a particular war.","start":2192.044,"stop":2205.909,"duration":13.87},{"text":"But it's not the magnitude or the sincerity of the objection which gives rise to the distinction, it is its nature.","start":2205.909,"stop":2215.776,"duration":9.87},{"text":"Congress could reasonably conclude in the exercise of its constitutionally granted power to raise and maintain arms.","start":2215.776,"stop":2226.395,"duration":10.62},{"text":"That a viable Government cannot allow political dissent to excuse a person from the duties, which it feels it must impose on all persons of the same class.","start":2226.395,"stop":2240.538,"duration":14.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Solicitor, are you arguing that even if assistance claims were religious, the Government could nevertheless deny him an exemption because it doesn't oppose all wars?","start":2240.538,"stop":2251.605,"duration":11.07}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice.","start":2251.605,"stop":2253.059,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But you don't have to reach that point here in this case because I gather you claim his position isn't religious anyway?","start":2253.059,"stop":2260.251,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Mr. Justice.","start":2260.251,"stop":2261.095,"duration":0.84},{"text":"The statute as I see it has two conditions in it by reason of religious training and belief which Sisson doesn't meet by his own assertion is constitutionally opposed to participation in war in any form.","start":2261.095,"stop":2277.457,"duration":16.36},{"text":"And Sisson by his own assertion does not meet the second ground.","start":2277.457,"stop":2283.42,"duration":5.96},{"text":"I don't think it makes any difference whether his reason for not meeting the second ground is religious or intellectual and philosophical.","start":2283.42,"stop":2294.796,"duration":11.38},{"text":"Now, I would point out that Bond case decided by Judge Weigel --","start":2294.796,"stop":2299.144,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But if we, if we said that his position was in religious in any event that's the end of it --","start":2299.144,"stop":2306.206,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be -- then you would not need to decide the war in any form at issue.","start":2306.206,"stop":2311.763,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Solicitor, supposed that not this case but there is an establish religion that we will both agree is offensive and they say the war in Vietnam is bad for some reason and were against it.","start":2311.763,"stop":2325.187,"duration":13.42},{"text":"We urge all participants not to participate that would be sufficient, would it?","start":2325.187,"stop":2333.258,"duration":8.07}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, I would --","start":2333.258,"stop":2334.518,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That case there.","start":2334.518,"stop":2335.277,"duration":0.76},{"text":"I'm only trying to take here the statute report.","start":2335.277,"stop":2336.443,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a -- this is a hard case, which fortunately isn't here.","start":2336.443,"stop":2340.273,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2340.273,"stop":2341,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"But I would take the position that Congress can draw the line and say that it recognizes religious objection only when it is based on opposition to war in any form.","start":2341,"stop":2353.573,"duration":12.57},{"text":"That is what it has said in the statute.","start":2353.573,"stop":2355.982,"duration":2.41},{"text":"I don't know any reason why it shouldn't be taken at face value.","start":2355.982,"stop":2361.724,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the excuse?","start":2361.724,"stop":2363.236,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I recognized that if that case came and in some ways it's almost presented in the Bond case.","start":2363.236,"stop":2369.972,"duration":6.74},{"text":"The Bond case involved a sincere catholic who following certain teachings of the church with respect to just and unjust wars, concluded that this was unjust war and that he could not participate in it and I need not make it plain that I have no question whatever about the sincerity of his beliefs or about the sincerity of Sisson's beliefs.","start":2369.972,"stop":2394.88,"duration":24.91},{"text":"It is our position that this is a judgment, which not only has been made by Congress, but which it was proper for Congress to make.","start":2394.88,"stop":2404.345,"duration":9.46},{"text":"We have not only the First Amendment, we have the raise and maintain armies clause and Congress has said that two qualified for a conscientious objection, exemption you must be opposed to war in any form.","start":2404.345,"stop":2423.408,"duration":19.06},{"text":"And I would suppose that that would be true, even though Congress repealed the religious training and belief exception which it seems to me they might well do Australian-Great Britain get along without it but that's a matter for the judgment of Congress.","start":2423.408,"stop":2442.617,"duration":19.21},{"text":"Supposed that Congress did eliminate religious training and belief but simply said as the Australians and the English do is opposed to war in any form.","start":2442.617,"stop":2453.415,"duration":10.8},{"text":"It seems to me, it would not help the claimant to say, “I'm not opposed to war at any form.","start":2453.415,"stop":2458.842,"duration":5.43},{"text":"I am only opposed to this war but I am opposed on religious grounds,” and brought in all kinds of documentation to show that he had sound religious grounds for doing it.","start":2458.842,"stop":2470.412,"duration":11.57},{"text":"He not only still would not come within the statute but it would be my submission and I know this is a difficult illusive area.","start":2470.412,"stop":2481.169,"duration":10.76},{"text":"But it would be my submission that there's nothing in the Constitution which can't properly be regarded as restricting Congress in making that judgment.","start":2481.169,"stop":2490.672,"duration":9.5}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the exclusionary language in the statute that you referred to in the Bond case, I think that followed the amended language.","start":2490.672,"stop":2500.666,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the --","start":2500.666,"stop":2500.954,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What shall not to --","start":2500.954,"stop":2501.748,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute now says, it's in the Welsh --","start":2501.748,"stop":2512.586,"duration":10.84}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"The Welsh case, excuse me.","start":2512.586,"stop":2514.897,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, it's on page 3 of the Sisson brief and this is the way it is now.","start":2514.897,"stop":2524.509,"duration":9.61},{"text":"Nothing contained in this title shall be construed to require any person to be subject to combatant training, who by reason of religious training and belief is conscientiously opposed to participation in war in any form as used in this subsection the term religious training and belief does not include essentially political, sociological, or philosophical views or a merely personal moral code.","start":2524.509,"stop":2553.653,"duration":29.14},{"text":"Now that in line is not only a thin one at best but in particular cases it can become extraordinarily thin.","start":2553.653,"stop":2563.275,"duration":9.62},{"text":"But it seems to me, that there is room for a line there that Congress has drawn the line.","start":2563.275,"stop":2570.785,"duration":7.51},{"text":"In this case, there's no problem about its being close to the line or not.","start":2570.785,"stop":2575.2,"duration":4.41},{"text":"It is asserted that he does not base his claim on religious training and relief.","start":2575.2,"stop":2584.2,"duration":9},{"text":"And in the Sisson case, we think because on the agreed statement of facts to use Judge Wyzanski's phrase, “The appellee does not qualify under the statute either by reason of religious training or relief -- and belief or by reason to opposition to war in any form.","start":2584.2,"stop":2610.222,"duration":26.02},{"text":"We submit that the judgment of the District Court should be reversed and that the case should be remanded to that Court and here Mr. Chief Justice, I come to what I think the was your procedural point with directions to enter judgment on the verdict.","start":2610.222,"stop":2627.02,"duration":16.8}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Solicitor.","start":2627.02,"stop":2633.195,"duration":6.18},{"text":"Mr. Flym.","start":2633.195,"stop":2634.768,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":2634.768,"stop":2641.364,"duration":6.6},{"text":"I'd like first to address myself to the question whether the decision arresting judgment of conviction was in fact entered by the court below.","start":2641.364,"stop":2651.793,"duration":10.43},{"text":"I note parenthetically that the Government's brief at pages 7 and 8 states, “Appellees motion which the trial judge granted purported to be in and was treated by the District Court as a motion in arrest of judgment.","start":2651.793,"stop":2665.212,"duration":13.42}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you --","start":2665.212,"stop":2665.322,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"This --","start":2665.322,"stop":2665.461,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- raise your voice a little bit counsel.","start":2665.461,"stop":2666.779,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2666.779,"stop":2669.139,"duration":2.36},{"text":"It was submitted in accordance with the times spelled out in Rule 34 or the making of such motions after the jury's verdict of guilty.","start":2669.139,"stop":2677.804,"duration":8.66},{"text":"A ground on which the motion rested but the indictment did not charge an offense similarly fell within the traditional scope of such motions is expressly recognized in Rule 34.","start":2677.804,"stop":2689.42,"duration":11.62},{"text":"I have assumed for proposes of my brief an argument before this Court today, that the Government agreed with our position that what the judge in fact granted was a motion in arrest of judgment.","start":2689.42,"stop":2703.096,"duration":13.68},{"text":"I think that assumption is supported by the record.","start":2703.096,"stop":2706.357,"duration":3.26},{"text":"On the date when the verdict of guilty was rendered by the jury, the judge said, this appears at page 197 of the record.","start":2706.357,"stop":2719.282,"duration":12.93},{"text":"He said March 31st as the date for sentencing that is, “Had no motion in arrest of judgment then filed and there was no guarantee at any such motion would be filed by Sisson in this case.","start":2719.282,"stop":2734.246,"duration":14.96},{"text":"Sentencing would have occurred on March 31st.","start":2734.246,"stop":2737.615,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Could that motion had been made one of the rules after the entry of the judgments.","start":2737.615,"stop":2744.508,"duration":6.89},{"text":"In other words, it's about enough to allow a motion an arrest of the execution of the judgment?","start":2744.508,"stop":2750.91,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Rule 34 expressly limits the time within which a motion in arrest of judgment can be made.","start":2750.91,"stop":2758.449,"duration":7.54}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Between the --","start":2758.449,"stop":2758.56,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"It will carry the 10 days following the verdict guilty or within such further time as the Court allow us.","start":2758.56,"stop":2767.64,"duration":9.08},{"text":"But as of the date of the jury's verdict, there were 10 days within which the motion could be filed.","start":2767.64,"stop":2775.041,"duration":7.4},{"text":"If no such motion was filed on March 31st, the expiration of the 10-day period sentencing was to occur.","start":2775.041,"stop":2784.031,"duration":8.99},{"text":"Moreover, the docket in the case is reproduced at the beginning of the record on appeal at pages 3, and 4, and 5 as a matter of fact as an indication spelling out the judgment the decision of the District Court as follows.","start":2784.031,"stop":2803.1,"duration":19.07},{"text":"The defendant with his counsel and Government counsel present, the Court reads its opinion granting defendants motion in arrest of judgment pursuing to Rule 34 by the federal rules of criminal procedure.","start":2803.1,"stop":2814.823,"duration":11.72},{"text":"Excerpts quoted below, “In the words of Rule 34 the indictment of Sisson does not charge an offense.”","start":2814.823,"stop":2821.133,"duration":6.31},{"text":"This Court's decision arresting a judgment of conviction for inefficiency of the indictment is based upon the invalidity of the statute upon which the indictment is founded within the meaning of those phrases as used in 18 U.S.C. Section 3731.","start":2821.133,"stop":2835.116,"duration":13.98},{"text":"Then, the century in the docket continues and concludes Court orders this decision and this Court's order granting defendants Sisson's motion in arrest of judgment enter forthwith.","start":2835.116,"stop":2851.322,"duration":16.21},{"text":"On the question of the scope of the statute in conferring jurisdiction upon this Court on appeal, on direct appeal from judgments of the District Court, granting a motion in arrest of judgment.","start":2851.322,"stop":2867.57,"duration":16.25},{"text":"We concur with the position of the Government that indeed this Court does have jurisdiction under the motion in arrest of judgment provision of Section 3731 of the Criminal Appeals Act.","start":2867.57,"stop":2882.326,"duration":14.76},{"text":"In addition, it is our position that the Government saw an argument with respect to the other two clauses the plea in bar, as well as leave motion dismissing an indictment.","start":2882.326,"stop":2900.983,"duration":18.66},{"text":"Really, really is quite persuasive that the intent of the draftsmen of the Criminal Appeals Act was precisely to confer upon this Court jurisdiction in all cases which were not precluded by the Constitution by reason of the Double Jeopardy Clause.","start":2900.983,"stop":2920.663,"duration":19.68},{"text":"Now, I have in mind for instance and I'm simply selecting randomly on page 22 of the Government's brief.","start":2920.663,"stop":2933.453,"duration":12.79},{"text":"There is a quotation from Senator Bacon, which he indicates that, “The Jeopardy Clause was inserted in the motion in bar subdivision out of an abundance of caution.”","start":2933.453,"stop":2948.302,"duration":14.85},{"text":"The caution, I suggest to the Court in context were simply that they wanted to be quite clear that they were not purporting to grand jurisdiction in cases which are constitutionally proscribe.","start":2948.302,"stop":2962.651,"duration":14.35},{"text":"Now, as a reference to the purpose which the statute was intended to serve on that same page, page 22 of the brief.","start":2962.651,"stop":2969.882,"duration":7.23},{"text":"The purpose was simply to meet the problem of having District Court Judge's dismissing criminal prosecutions.","start":2969.882,"stop":2980.343,"duration":10.46},{"text":"In particular there was a case against -- Cherry Meat Packers.","start":2980.343,"stop":2984.944,"duration":4.6},{"text":"The Court dismissed the proceedings and the Government was powerless to do anything about it.","start":2984.944,"stop":2989.688,"duration":4.74},{"text":"And Congress wanted to ensure that that sort of a result simply could not have it.","start":2989.688,"stop":2995.93,"duration":6.24},{"text":"It wanted to provide review in this Court to ensure that those sorts of decisions would be reviewed by the Court and I don't think there's a shred of evidence which indicates that the Congress intended by providing various loopholes to make it possible by supposedly, well, a district judge bent on circumventing the appeals provision of the Criminal Appeals Act.","start":2995.93,"stop":3018.666,"duration":22.74},{"text":"To simply avoid this result namely of providing review in this Court by for instance permitting, well the procedure which was followed in this case.","start":3018.666,"stop":3028.359,"duration":9.69},{"text":"That it seems to me that the present cases the prototype of the situation, which the draftsmen of the Criminal Appeals Act could not possibly have intended to result in precluding review by this Court.","start":3028.359,"stop":3039.92,"duration":11.56},{"text":"That is simply would be much too easy to circumvent the purpose of the draftsmen of the Act.","start":3039.92,"stop":3045.04,"duration":5.12},{"text":"Now on page 23, Senator Nelson expressly says again I'm quoting the quotation, elsewhere said that, “The plain bar section, it was made clear out of the extreme caution that where the defendant has been put in jeopardy, he cannot be reindicted.”","start":3045.04,"stop":3061.559,"duration":16.52},{"text":"The emphasis again was on the question whether the defendant having filed whatever motions been filed.","start":3061.559,"stop":3068.887,"duration":7.33},{"text":"Having that motion granted by the Court whether he could be reindicted and I don't think, there's any question or is there any suggestion by the Government that in circumstances where a defendant files a motion in bar or a motion in arrest of judgment that he could in fact be reindicted if the motion were granted in subsequently that decision were vacated.","start":3068.887,"stop":3091.107,"duration":22.22},{"text":"Now, the Government at page 25 quotes Justice Holmes in the case of United States against Macdonald and indeed, Justice Holmes refers to judgments rendered before the moment of jeopardy is reach.","start":3091.107,"stop":3112.464,"duration":21.36},{"text":"What is omitted immediately succeeding the quotation that is the text includes a citation to the decision in Kepner against United States at 195 U.S. and in that decision Justice Holmes we quote from him in our brief, they declare that he consider the double jeopardy question to be a very limited one.","start":3112.464,"stop":3135.472,"duration":23.01},{"text":"That is he pointed out there are numerous circumstances in which a man can be retried after having once been tried and found guilty by a jury without contravening the double jeopardy safeguard in the Constitution.","start":3135.472,"stop":3150.03,"duration":14.56},{"text":"It won't leave where the point anymore, I would like again to refer to the testimony of Senator Knox which is quoted at pages 26 and 27 of the Government's brief in which Senator Knox refers to all of the motions that is the merit to the indictment, the motion to quash or set aside the indictment, motion and arrest of judgment and in judgment sustaining defendant's plea in bar.","start":3150.03,"stop":3179.22,"duration":29.19},{"text":"And he refers to all of these motions, as motions the effect of which is to defeat jeopardy.","start":3179.22,"stop":3185.946,"duration":6.73},{"text":"I believe that's accurate in glossing of what is --","start":3185.946,"stop":3188.522,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You want us to affirm this judgment?","start":3188.522,"stop":3191.319,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3191.319,"stop":3191.976,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Where's that leave your client?","start":3191.976,"stop":3194.418,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"If the judgment is affirmed?","start":3194.418,"stop":3195.849,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Uh-huh.","start":3195.849,"stop":3196.994,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I believe that the conviction is set aside.","start":3196.994,"stop":3202.486,"duration":5.49},{"text":"That is the judgment of the Court is --","start":3202.486,"stop":3205.143,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Arrested.","start":3205.143,"stop":3206.092,"duration":0.95},{"text":"That's all the judgment said.","start":3206.092,"stop":3208.195,"duration":2.1},{"text":"That's all the opinion said.","start":3208.195,"stop":3210.411,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3210.411,"stop":3211.187,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That he stand.","start":3211.187,"stop":3212.255,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the judgment is arrested, Your Honor.","start":3212.255,"stop":3214.897,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But he's still there but is arrested.","start":3214.897,"stop":3217.043,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Right and --","start":3217.043,"stop":3219.055,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I am just wondering, how would you report that if somebody says if you have been convicted how you would report that, while arrested?","start":3219.055,"stop":3226.512,"duration":7.46}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, well --","start":3226.512,"stop":3230.241,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean you're so busy giving this Court jurisdiction but I'm just wondering what you are doing with it?","start":3230.241,"stop":3237.766,"duration":7.53}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, so far as we're concerned, Your Honor, quite frankly, I'm not prepared to respond to that.","start":3237.766,"stop":3244.26,"duration":6.49},{"text":"I haven't thought of the problem but I will represent that will be satisfied with -- when were judgment in this Court saying affirmed, I think, we can deal with the problem once -- once that action is taken.","start":3244.26,"stop":3259.906,"duration":15.65},{"text":"I would -- by way of context, there just isn't enough time remaining today to deal with all of the issues particularly the First Amendment issues, selective objective question.","start":3259.906,"stop":3271.748,"duration":11.84},{"text":"I would like to refer, if I may, to some of the statement made by Solicitor General Griswold because I consider that some of the difficulties in hearing in this case arise from assumptions made by the Solicitor General, which are not dealt with it at all in either of the briefs.","start":3271.748,"stop":3295.579,"duration":23.83},{"text":"That is -- the assumptions for instance is that when Congress acts that somehow there is a presumption which arises from the action of Congress, which is sufficient to simply overcome whatever claims an individual might make.","start":3295.579,"stop":3315.559,"duration":19.98},{"text":"We're certainly not challenging our system of Government in this case.","start":3315.559,"stop":3320.156,"duration":4.6},{"text":"We're not challenging democracy or majority rule.","start":3320.156,"stop":3325.023,"duration":4.87},{"text":"We're not requesting that this Court imposed its judgments and substitute it for the judgment of the legislature of Congress.","start":3325.023,"stop":3333.983,"duration":8.96}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Then you do not accept his extension and application of the -- of your position to, for example, the social security payments or unemployment compensation or taxes?","start":3333.983,"stop":3350.692,"duration":16.71}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":3350.692,"stop":3351.249,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think this is just limited to the war problem?","start":3351.249,"stop":3354.679,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue presented before this Court is limited solely to the question or the man can be deprived of his liberty and compelled to kill conceivably.","start":3354.679,"stop":3364.859,"duration":10.18}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how do we know that he is going to be compelled to kill?","start":3364.859,"stop":3367.248,"duration":2.39},{"text":"That's an issue that didn't get discussed very much but he might wind up working in the embassy in Paris.","start":3367.248,"stop":3373.791,"duration":6.54}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true.","start":3373.791,"stop":3374.558,"duration":0.77},{"text":"That's true he might.","start":3374.558,"stop":3375.663,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Then he does not --","start":3375.663,"stop":3375.843,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"But initially --","start":3375.843,"stop":3376.184,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"-- not kill anybody?","start":3376.184,"stop":3377.598,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3377.598,"stop":3377.983,"duration":0.39},{"text":"Initially at the very least, we're only certain that he was to be deprived of his liberty.","start":3377.983,"stop":3382.724,"duration":4.74},{"text":"I would submit that that's efficient for purposes of distinguishing this case from a tax case.","start":3382.724,"stop":3389.668,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3389.668,"stop":3389.817,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"It is --","start":3389.817,"stop":3390.332,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, wait a minute let me see.","start":3390.332,"stop":3392.602,"duration":2.27},{"text":"You haven't been concerned as I understood you the thrust of your case with his being deprived of his liberty but being made to fight a war.","start":3392.602,"stop":3400.223,"duration":7.62},{"text":"Now, assume he was sent to Paris to work in the embassy, do you have a case?","start":3400.223,"stop":3409.905,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so, Your Honor.","start":3409.905,"stop":3410.551,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you have a complaint?","start":3410.551,"stop":3411.36,"duration":0.81},{"text":"Do you have a compliant?","start":3411.36,"stop":3413.322,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I think at this point, we do.","start":3413.322,"stop":3415.089,"duration":1.77},{"text":"That is, with -- it is somewhat difficult to speculate about where he might have been sent, that is we have statistics showing that he had two out of three chances of being sent to Vietnam at least.","start":3415.089,"stop":3427.249,"duration":12.16},{"text":"But what happened was that he refused to submit to induction and he refused to submit to obey an order which was issued to him.","start":3427.249,"stop":3436.311,"duration":9.06},{"text":"And the Government asserts in various places that whether this conduct is criminal or not depends on the validity of the order.","start":3436.311,"stop":3447.131,"duration":10.82},{"text":"Now, we assert that the order as such, which precedes any assignment of the conscript to any field of duty whether to Paris or Vietnam, or any other locations.","start":3447.131,"stop":3460.234,"duration":13.1},{"text":"We assert that that order was in it of itself invalid for variety of reasons.","start":3460.234,"stop":3466.444,"duration":6.21},{"text":"I would in the time remaining this afternoon, simply like to address myself to two points.","start":3466.444,"stop":3473.071,"duration":6.63},{"text":"One will be in passing.","start":3473.071,"stop":3475.829,"duration":2.76},{"text":"I'll refer to recent book written by a man named Raoul Berger entitled “Congress against the Supreme Court” in which the point is made I think quite convincingly.","start":3475.829,"stop":3491.003,"duration":15.17},{"text":"The judicial review in this Court is not a matter of user patient by this Court but was something intended very definitely by the framers of the Constitution, precisely to provide a safeguard against the encroachment of individual liberty by Congress.","start":3491.003,"stop":3513.228,"duration":22.22},{"text":"I would only like to refer to two quotations; one is from page 31 of this book its a 1969 book by Jefferson.","start":3513.228,"stop":3526.054,"duration":12.83},{"text":"Jefferson in 1781 stated, “That 173 despots would surely be as oppressive as one and elective despotism was not the Government we fought for.”","start":3526.054,"stop":3542.615,"duration":16.56},{"text":"Similarly, Madison in dealing with the purpose of the Bill of Rights stated, “These Amendments are incorporated into the Constitution, independent, tribunals of justice will consider themselves in a peculiar manner the guardians of those rights.","start":3542.615,"stop":3561.796,"duration":19.18},{"text":"It will be and impenetrable ball work against every assumption of power in the legislative or executive.","start":3561.796,"stop":3569.516,"duration":7.72},{"text":"Now, the notion that the Federal Congress might arrogate to itself, powers and infringing individual liberty was something of which the framers was -- were very, very conscious.","start":3569.516,"stop":3584.813,"duration":15.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3584.813,"stop":3585.33,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"They were concerned principally about Congress, the Federal Congress.","start":3585.33,"stop":3589.423,"duration":4.09},{"text":"They were not particularly concern about state legislatures.","start":3589.423,"stop":3593.278,"duration":3.86},{"text":"They have faith in their state legislators.","start":3593.278,"stop":3595.05,"duration":1.77},{"text":"They knew but they knew nothing whatsoever about this new organ.","start":3595.05,"stop":3600.1,"duration":5.05},{"text":"This Federal Legislature that was to sit at times 1,000 miles away from some parts of this vast land.","start":3600.1,"stop":3608.396,"duration":8.3},{"text":"And the people were afraid that precisely the Federal Government would reach out and deprive them of fundamental liberties.","start":3608.396,"stop":3615.166,"duration":6.77},{"text":"For this purpose, this Court was vested with judicial review with the power of deciding where the Congress has exceeded the limits of its power, of the limited delegated powers conferred by the Constitution.","start":3615.166,"stop":3628.748,"duration":13.58},{"text":"This doctrine was asserted repeatedly throughout the time of the ratification of framing of the Constitution that is set on the verdict book.","start":3628.748,"stop":3637.495,"duration":8.75},{"text":"It was reiterated by this Court in Luther against Borden in the middle of 19th century.","start":3637.495,"stop":3645.406,"duration":7.91},{"text":"The only other point, I wish to make is the repeated insistence by the Solicitor General to history that on the basis of the history surrounding the adoption of the Bill of Rights.","start":3645.406,"stop":3660.488,"duration":15.08},{"text":"There is no basis for this Court concluding that religion is coextensive with the rights of conscience.","start":3660.488,"stop":3666.271,"duration":5.78},{"text":"I submit and I do it diffidently I was one of the students and this is a great man, vast knowledge of taxation certainly but I respectfully suggest that his knowledge -- the scope of the religion protection is not accurate, it's simply is not accurate.","start":3666.271,"stop":3688.804,"duration":22.53},{"text":"I refer for instance to the part of our brief at pages 97 through 102.","start":3688.804,"stop":3699.894,"duration":11.09},{"text":"In particular, I have reference to ratification statements, free ratification statements, that is before the Bill of Rights was in existence, that is I posit it to this Court the situation where there is no Bill of Rights where there is not First Amendment to be construed.","start":3699.894,"stop":3719.07,"duration":19.18},{"text":"And I ask this Court whether in that circumstance this Court could reach the conclusion that religion does not extend to the right of conscience or that the Constitution was intended to deprive individuals of the protection of religion, the free exercise of religion.","start":3719.07,"stop":3738.029,"duration":18.96},{"text":"I refer in particular to declarations of rights made by the conventions of New York, Rhode Island, North Carolina, and Virginia.","start":3738.029,"stop":3751.376,"duration":13.35},{"text":"These declarations assert the existence of certain inalienable rights and make it very clear that the Constitution was being ratified only with the expressed understanding that these rights were not infringed by the Constitution.","start":3751.376,"stop":3766.723,"duration":15.35},{"text":"That was prior to the adoption of the Bill of Rights.","start":3766.723,"stop":3770.143,"duration":3.42},{"text":"One of these rights was, “That the people have an equal and natural and an alienable right freely and peaceably to exercise their religion according to the dictates of their conscience and that no religious sect or society ought to be favored or established by law in preference of others.”","start":3770.143,"stop":3787.366,"duration":17.22}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"How does that get into this case?","start":3787.366,"stop":3789.919,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"It gets into this case in this way Your Honor.","start":3789.919,"stop":3793.013,"duration":3.09},{"text":"The argument of the Government relies on the proposition that somehow the word religion has grown beyond its intended scope.","start":3793.013,"stop":3801.927,"duration":8.91}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you claim religious exemption here?","start":3801.927,"stop":3804.632,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Are you now arguing for religious exemption?","start":3804.632,"stop":3807.545,"duration":2.91}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"On a constitutional basis, we always have.","start":3807.545,"stop":3810.303,"duration":2.76},{"text":"That is it isn't -- isn't an inaccurate statement to describe Sisson as a selective nonreligious objector.","start":3810.303,"stop":3819.02,"duration":8.72},{"text":"He is a selective nonreligious conscientious objector and the very necessity for making that distinction between the religious objector or rather nonreligious objecting -- nonreligious conscientious objector is the fact that the Act, as the Solicitor General so eagerly defended it, makes that distinction.","start":3819.02,"stop":3837.462,"duration":18.44},{"text":"It does not extend the scope of the exemption in the Act to the full measure of protection and afforded to religion under the First Amendment.","start":3837.462,"stop":3848.458,"duration":11}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll postpone till morning.","start":3848.458,"stop":3852.288,"duration":3.83}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 21, 1970","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger1/oral_argument_audio/15003","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Flym, you may pick up where you left off.","start":0,"stop":3.394,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3.394,"stop":11.39,"duration":8},{"text":"I think we left off suggesting that if there were no Bill of Rights at all, this Court would nonetheless be required by the constitution as adopted by the framers, by the state ratifying conventions as they understood the constitution would require this Court nonetheless to protect the individual rights of citizens –","start":11.39,"stop":36.302,"duration":24.91}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You say as they understood it?","start":36.302,"stop":39.423,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":39.423,"stop":41.078,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you have a particular focus to put that on?","start":41.078,"stop":43.943,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, I do.","start":43.943,"stop":45.477,"duration":1.53},{"text":"On page 98 through 99 of our brief -– I'm sorry, it's page 100 through 101.","start":45.477,"stop":57.229,"duration":11.75},{"text":"We quote from a statement made by the Rhode Island Ratifying Convention, which is virtually identical, I think there are very minor changes in language that is almost identical to the statements made by the North Carolina and Virginia Ratifying Conventions, I'm sorry.","start":57.229,"stop":81.177,"duration":23.95},{"text":"And the statement states, that is that's just a very small portion of the statement made by the Ratifying Convention.","start":81.177,"stop":90.264,"duration":9.09},{"text":"The Ratifying Convention said –-","start":90.264,"stop":92.453,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Made by who?","start":92.453,"stop":93.614,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"By the Ratifying Convention of the State of Rhode Island, Your Honor, almost identical to the statement made by the Ratifying Convention of the State of North Carolina, as well as the State of Virginia.","start":93.614,"stop":104.974,"duration":11.36},{"text":"These statements expressly asserted that ratification of the constitution was based on an expressed understanding that it did not infringe unalienable rights of individual citizens.","start":104.974,"stop":121.673,"duration":16.7},{"text":"The fourth paragraph, the fourth proposition stated in that ratifying statement is that religion or the duty which we owe to our creator in the manner of discharging it can be directed only by reason and conviction and not by force or violence.","start":121.673,"stop":141.393,"duration":19.72},{"text":"And therefore, all men have an equal, natural and inalienable right to the free exercise of religion according to the dictates of conscience and that no particular religious sect or society ought to be favored or established by law in preference to others.","start":141.393,"stop":157.862,"duration":16.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What page is it on your brief?","start":157.862,"stop":159.72,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"100 through 101, Your Honor, the bottom of 100 through the top of 101.","start":159.72,"stop":165.781,"duration":6.06},{"text":"That statement is virtually identical to the statement made from the Ratifying Convention of the State of New York.","start":165.781,"stop":172.064,"duration":6.28},{"text":"I accorded that at the end of the argument yesterday.","start":172.064,"stop":175.338,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"When did Rhode Island get around to ratifying the constitution?","start":175.338,"stop":178.059,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Pretty late in the game, wouldn't it?","start":178.059,"stop":179.307,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Very late, Your Honor.","start":179.307,"stop":180.499,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":180.499,"stop":182.779,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure, but I think among the four states represented in these statements, it's perfectly clear that there would have been no ratification of the constitution but for the expressed understanding that these rights were safeguarded.","start":182.779,"stop":198.209,"duration":15.43},{"text":"That is, there was no need for the Bill of Rights to protect religion as understood by the persons who drafted and who ratified the constitution.","start":198.209,"stop":207.853,"duration":9.64},{"text":"It's true that a Bill of Rights were subsequently enacted but Madison explained, and that's quoted at the bottom of 98 through top of 99, “Although I know whenever the great rights, the trial by jury, freedom of the press, of liberty of conscience come in question in that body, the invasion of them is resisted by able advocates.","start":207.853,"stop":228.975,"duration":21.12},{"text":"Yet, their magna carta does not contain any one provision for the security of those rights respecting which the people of America are most alarmed.”","start":228.975,"stop":238.171,"duration":9.2},{"text":"The freedom –-","start":238.171,"stop":238.73,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the only reference you have?","start":238.73,"stop":241.25,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I have –- these are just random –-","start":241.25,"stop":243.042,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean to this?","start":243.042,"stop":243.732,"duration":0.69},{"text":"I don't see anything in here that necessarily leads to the conclusion that they thought a man could get out of going to the army constitutionally because of his religious belief?","start":243.732,"stop":255.412,"duration":11.68}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's a separate question, Your Honor.","start":255.412,"stop":257.771,"duration":2.36},{"text":"It certainly is related and that's why I mentioned it at this point, but I'm simply addressing myself now to the assertion made by the government that religion does not mean conscience.","start":257.771,"stop":270.317,"duration":12.55},{"text":"And I think that's clearly wrong from the standpoint of history.","start":270.317,"stop":273.999,"duration":3.68},{"text":"I can understand the government's inclination so to construe the protection of religion in the Bill of Rights.","start":273.999,"stop":281.574,"duration":7.57},{"text":"I understand why they would like to limit it, but it's just flatly inaccurate as a matter of history.","start":281.574,"stop":286.838,"duration":5.26},{"text":"That's just not what they understood 180 years ago.","start":286.838,"stop":290.807,"duration":3.97},{"text":"What we're calling for is not something which would destroy orderly government at all.","start":290.807,"stop":295.769,"duration":4.96},{"text":"Obviously, what would be most destructive of orderly government would be if the constitution were ignored, and we want the constitution enforced.","start":295.769,"stop":305.527,"duration":9.76},{"text":"That is, the constitution says certain things about what powers Congress have, and I will come very quickly to that central question.","start":305.527,"stop":314.746,"duration":9.22},{"text":"That is, what power did Congress receive through the constitution to draft individuals, whether in peace or in order.","start":314.746,"stop":325.151,"duration":10.41},{"text":"That's the central issue.","start":325.151,"stop":326.045,"duration":0.89},{"text":"Obviously, if the constitution did not delegate this power to Congress, Congress doesn't have it.","start":326.045,"stop":331.315,"duration":5.27},{"text":"Even if Congress would like to have it, even if Congress thinks that it is absolutely indispensable in its judgment to have that power, if that power was not conferred by the constitution, it's perfectly plain they don't have the power.","start":331.315,"stop":343.93,"duration":12.62},{"text":"The constitution sets the limits of the power that were in fact conferred to Congress.","start":343.93,"stop":349.3,"duration":5.37},{"text":"Now, I'm simply –-","start":349.3,"stop":349.478,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So it's your idea that anything –- anytime a man believes its wrong to go to war, it couldn't be conscripted that was almost necessary to do away with conscription, wouldn't it?","start":349.478,"stop":363.637,"duration":14.16}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not our proposition, Your Honor.","start":363.637,"stop":366.719,"duration":3.08},{"text":"That is –- I think there's a very important distinction between a man who acts on the basis of conscience that is who simply can't obey the order.","start":366.719,"stop":381.064,"duration":14.35},{"text":"That's on that system.","start":381.064,"stop":383.625,"duration":2.56},{"text":"And a man who thinks, well, it'd be a bad policy to follow, to go fight a war in Vietnam --","start":383.625,"stop":389.837,"duration":6.21}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But they were allowed to distinguish between the two, wouldn't it, when you begin to probe the line?","start":389.837,"stop":394.169,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, but that's a very customary function in law, that is we're constantly –- the Courts, that is –- are constantly about the business of establishing where the man intended to do something around it, but just don't know how to avoid that.","start":394.169,"stop":409.938,"duration":15.77},{"text":"But –-","start":409.938,"stop":410.022,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well counsel, this familiar history is very interesting but let's bring it down to the particular case, and if I may put to you again the question I suggested yesterday, would his rights of conscience be violated if in fact he were taken in and assigned as a security guard at the American Embassy in Paris for the entire tour of his duty?","start":410.022,"stop":432.912,"duration":22.89},{"text":"Would his rights of conscience be invaded?","start":432.912,"stop":436.076,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so, Your Honor.","start":436.076,"stop":437.351,"duration":1.27},{"text":"But is –-","start":437.351,"stop":437.436,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought his objection was to the particular war being conducted in Vietnam?","start":437.436,"stop":443.437,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in a sense, that's true, but –-","start":443.437,"stop":447.736,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is it all military service or just the war in Vietnam, I wanted it that clear?","start":447.736,"stop":451.345,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's the military service.","start":451.345,"stop":452.954,"duration":1.61},{"text":"That is, he disobeyed an order.","start":452.954,"stop":455.955,"duration":3},{"text":"He disobeyed that order on the basis of his conviction that the order was invalid.","start":455.955,"stop":462.658,"duration":6.7},{"text":"Now at this point, I really don't think that the question is whether his subjective belief was well founded.","start":462.658,"stop":469.49,"duration":6.83},{"text":"At least the threshold question is whether from an objective point of view, he was right, whether the order was valid.","start":469.49,"stop":476.119,"duration":6.63},{"text":"Did Congress in fact have the power to issue the order to this man that he report for induction because if Congress had no such power, simply to induct him into the army, then refusal to obey the order simply is not a criminal act.","start":476.119,"stop":493.643,"duration":17.52},{"text":"And that's independent of what he may have believed to doubt the Vietnam war or may not have believed.","start":493.643,"stop":499.389,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I have difficulty reconciling the points as you state them now and his own declaration which if I understood this record were all aimed at military activity in Vietnam.","start":499.389,"stop":516.857,"duration":17.47},{"text":"Did I misread the record?","start":516.857,"stop":518.727,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so, Your Honor.","start":518.727,"stop":520.544,"duration":1.82},{"text":"I respectfully suggest that from the outset, the motion is filed, the pre-trial motion is filed in this case squarely raised and the government has so recognized –- squarely raised that the initial question raised by the appellee was simply the power of Congress to issue that order to him, and he said no, Congress does not have that power.","start":520.544,"stop":544.328,"duration":23.78},{"text":"That is, if he had said nothing about his beliefs.","start":544.328,"stop":546.825,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"So I'm making a distinction between what he said and what you were saying, and I here at least see a difference?","start":546.825,"stop":554.187,"duration":7.36}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think, Your Honor.","start":554.187,"stop":556.664,"duration":2.48},{"text":"If I understand Your Honor's question that there's on the issues which were properly raised one issue, very definitely is the issue which the District Judge in fact based his decision upon.","start":556.664,"stop":572.123,"duration":15.46},{"text":"That is, the right of Johny Sisson to exercise freely his religion under the First Amendment.","start":572.123,"stop":579.267,"duration":7.14},{"text":"Or alternatively, the question, the issue whether the Selective Service Act of 1967 constitutes an establishment of religion.","start":579.267,"stop":589.325,"duration":10.06},{"text":"But that -- those were just two of the issues raised.","start":589.325,"stop":593.774,"duration":4.45},{"text":"We repeatedly reasserted and reasserted again in the motion in the rest of judgment.","start":593.774,"stop":599.693,"duration":5.92},{"text":"The threshold question obviously has to be whether the order issued to Johny Sisson was invalid.","start":599.693,"stop":605.704,"duration":6.01},{"text":"It might have been invalid for a number of technical reasons.","start":605.704,"stop":609.349,"duration":3.65},{"text":"Now, those technical reasons –- technical deficiencies in the order did not appear at the trial.","start":609.349,"stop":616.502,"duration":7.15},{"text":"If such deficiencies had appeared in fact, the case would not be here, certainly not on direct appeal.","start":616.502,"stop":623.592,"duration":7.09},{"text":"That is, the only questions presently being raised are questions bearing on the validity, constitutionality of that order.","start":623.592,"stop":632.103,"duration":8.51},{"text":"And the point we repeatedly stressed is that Congress just does not have power to conscript Sisson now.","start":632.103,"stop":640.965,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is because –- well, for a variety of reasons, to what reason in your submission though –- what particular reason are you submitting to us, I'm not very clear of that?","start":640.965,"stop":651.909,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"The particular reason, Your Honor, is that Congress is powered to raise and support arguments, which is the clause on which the government relies squarely, does not extend –- it is not an unlimited power.","start":651.909,"stop":665.57,"duration":13.66}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, alright, but then what -– and is limited in what respect where there's a vis-à-vis this case?","start":665.57,"stop":673.875,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"It is limited first of all to circumstances where an emergency exists.","start":673.875,"stop":681.643,"duration":7.77},{"text":"I know that that's somewhat vague, but I think by looking at the historical interpretation of Congress' power, we can derive very definite meaning as to what the framers of the constitution understood, what members of the first Congress understood by the power to raise and support arguments.","start":681.643,"stop":700.169,"duration":18.53},{"text":"Now –-","start":700.169,"stop":700.744,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, are you saying –- I know that perhaps –- I know in your brief, you say a variety of things but now, are you directing yourself to the argument that Congress has no constitutional power to enact a Selective Service Act when there is no declared war?","start":700.744,"stop":718.798,"duration":18.05},{"text":"Or are you saying it has no power to conscript people into the military when there is a situation going on, that is going on at Southeast Asia that violates international law?","start":718.798,"stop":733.988,"duration":15.19},{"text":"What are you -– to what point are you arguing now is what I don't quite get.","start":733.988,"stop":737.368,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the most solid point we have is the point that Congress has no power to draft in an emergency, which usually will mean the same thing as no power to draft absent to declaration of war.","start":737.368,"stop":754.649,"duration":17.28},{"text":"But the reason I think I don't –- we do not assert that in that form, that is that Congress can't conscript unless there's been a declaration of war, is that we concede that in a number of the emergencies, even if there were no declaration of war, Congress would have the power to conscript because I just don't believe that Congress is powerless to defend this country.","start":754.649,"stop":779.574,"duration":24.92},{"text":"This country must have the power to survive.","start":779.574,"stop":781.445,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then you're saying that there's no power to -- a constitutional power to conscript when there is no imminent danger of invasion of this country?","start":781.445,"stop":790.559,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not saying that either, Your Honor, but I am –-","start":790.559,"stop":794.024,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I really don't understand your argument.","start":794.024,"stop":795.36,"duration":1.34},{"text":"I gather though, the arguments you're making now has nothing to do with Sisson as such.","start":795.36,"stop":799.824,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":799.824,"stop":800.226,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This could be John Smith, who's a religious or irreligious person who has no particular ideas about Vietnam.","start":800.226,"stop":805.978,"duration":5.75},{"text":"You're talking about General Congressional Power?","start":805.978,"stop":807.998,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":807.998,"stop":809.783,"duration":1.78},{"text":"One example of an emergency, Your Honor, would be the Civil War.","start":809.783,"stop":813.7,"duration":3.92},{"text":"That is Civil War was not a declared war.","start":813.7,"stop":816.455,"duration":2.75},{"text":"It was an insurrection and indeed, Congress did adopt the Conscription Act.","start":816.455,"stop":822.222,"duration":5.77},{"text":"We're not challenging the power of Congress to –-","start":822.222,"stop":824.767,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What are you challenging?","start":824.767,"stop":826.864,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"We're saying that this war in the present circumstances just doesn't amount to the kind of emergency that must have been contemplated by the draftsmen of the constitution.","start":826.864,"stop":837.629,"duration":10.76},{"text":"That is –-","start":837.629,"stop":839.153,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They do not have a right to conscript in time of peace?","start":839.153,"stop":843.667,"duration":4.51}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":843.667,"stop":844.551,"duration":0.88},{"text":"Certainly, the –-","start":844.551,"stop":844.749,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the argument you're making?","start":844.749,"stop":846.463,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":846.463,"stop":847.76,"duration":1.3},{"text":"Time of peace again is somewhat misleading because that may be thought to mean the absence of a declaration of war.","start":847.76,"stop":855.983,"duration":8.22},{"text":"But I think what is at issue is the existence of an emergency that it makes it very, very clear that Congress has no choice, that it must conscript because if it doesn't conscript for a National Security is in a very mediate sense at stake.","start":855.983,"stop":873.305,"duration":17.32},{"text":"I don't think there's much ambiguity about what the power of Congress is meant for the first 150 years of the existence of this country.","start":873.305,"stop":882.204,"duration":8.9},{"text":"That is, peace time conscription as we know it is very, very recent in time, just –- it didn't take years.","start":882.204,"stop":888.548,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You deny the power –- you say power –- the Congress has no constitutional power to conscript from like universal military training?","start":888.548,"stop":897.694,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh definitely, Your Honor.","start":897.694,"stop":899.729,"duration":2.04},{"text":"But –-","start":899.729,"stop":900.115,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Definitely yes or definitely no?","start":900.115,"stop":901.009,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Definitely not, no.","start":901.009,"stop":902.255,"duration":1.25},{"text":"I just don't think they have that power.","start":902.255,"stop":904.162,"duration":1.91},{"text":"That is, if that had been even remotely suggested at the time that the constitution was ratified, absolutely no question but that that the constitution would not have been ratified.","start":904.162,"stop":915.816,"duration":11.65}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Flym, can you help me with my problem of getting conscience and legality together?","start":915.816,"stop":924.369,"duration":8.55}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll try, Your Honor.","start":924.369,"stop":926.248,"duration":1.88},{"text":"There are several steps to our argument.","start":926.248,"stop":930.395,"duration":4.15},{"text":"We begin with a broader story argument and with a relatively narrow argument based on Johnny Sisson.","start":930.395,"stop":939.698,"duration":9.3},{"text":"First argument is whether Congress has the power to draft anybody at this time.","start":939.698,"stop":945.508,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"So use of equip–- put in the same bowl the fact that I disagree with the legality of an act of Congress with my conscience –-","start":945.508,"stop":959.325,"duration":13.82}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"No, or –- no.","start":959.325,"stop":962.107,"duration":2.78},{"text":"That has been suggested two or three times.","start":962.107,"stop":964.352,"duration":2.25},{"text":"I hope I can make it very clear that that's not what we mean at all.","start":964.352,"stop":968.894,"duration":4.54},{"text":"That is, if Congress has the power to draft people in general, then the argument which we are now making is not relevant at all.","start":968.894,"stop":979.398,"duration":10.5},{"text":"It would remain a subsequent, a different question.","start":979.398,"stop":983.351,"duration":3.95},{"text":"That is, assuming that Congress has the power to draft the generality of men at this time, are they nonetheless restricted by the individual right of conscience, the right to free exercise of religion, so that they can't conscript certain classes of men.","start":983.351,"stop":1000.683,"duration":17.33}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But because I disagree, my conscience tells me I can abide by that law?","start":1000.683,"stop":1008.776,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh no, I don't think that that follows at all.","start":1008.776,"stop":1011.041,"duration":2.27},{"text":"You might disagree on political grounds, on economic grounds, sociological grounds.","start":1011.041,"stop":1015.073,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Why so -- I have a great problem with conscience and politics.","start":1015.073,"stop":1018.788,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all I can say, Your Honor, is again, I'd like to quote Madison and –- well, it was about the time of the –- he was at that time –-","start":1018.788,"stop":1028.69,"duration":9.9}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But you have already agreed that that argument can be made by anybody of the insisting?","start":1028.69,"stop":1033.529,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor -–","start":1033.529,"stop":1033.773,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I have to insist?","start":1033.773,"stop":1035.15,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it is a difficult problem.","start":1035.15,"stop":1038.507,"duration":3.36},{"text":"The judicial system is full of very, very difficult problems.","start":1038.507,"stop":1044.295,"duration":5.79},{"text":"Probably no more important questions arise and when the individual's rights are pitted against the government's power and --","start":1044.295,"stop":1052.575,"duration":8.28}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I agree.","start":1052.575,"stop":1053.655,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it is this Court, which is –-","start":1053.655,"stop":1055.107,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a difficult problem that tells me how being on duty in the embassy in Paris is aide in the Vietnam war, I have great difficulty with that.","start":1055.107,"stop":1065.374,"duration":10.27}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not the question at this point, Your Honor.","start":1065.374,"stop":1068.449,"duration":3.08},{"text":"If you would please –- the question is not where he would be assigned right now.","start":1068.449,"stop":1073.236,"duration":4.79},{"text":"The question of the power of the Congress to --","start":1073.236,"stop":1075.165,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course that he doesn't want to serve at any place in the military?","start":1075.165,"stop":1078.681,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether he wants to or not -–","start":1078.681,"stop":1079.418,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":1079.418,"stop":1080.533,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"-- whether he wants to or not is not the issue, not the issue.","start":1080.533,"stop":1085.904,"duration":5.37},{"text":"He might want to, and nonetheless his refusal might be justified if there was no power to issue that order.","start":1085.904,"stop":1092.157,"duration":6.25},{"text":"The threshold question is whether –-","start":1092.157,"stop":1093.197,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"They couldn't –- do you say that the Congress does not have the right to say that this man shall be put in the army and assigned to his hometown?","start":1093.197,"stop":1104.749,"duration":11.55}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly what we say, not just –-","start":1104.749,"stop":1106.8,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Then he objects military service?","start":1106.8,"stop":1109.808,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, I'm sorry, Your Honor.","start":1109.808,"stop":1112.379,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't understand how the point got involved in this case.","start":1112.379,"stop":1116.202,"duration":3.82},{"text":"It's elicit there and everybody I thought understood that this was a case of selective choosing of not fighting in the Vietnam war?","start":1116.202,"stop":1124.696,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, It got into this case because we raised it and we stressed it at every point.","start":1124.696,"stop":1130.662,"duration":5.97},{"text":"This is not a new point on appeal at all.","start":1130.662,"stop":1133.373,"duration":2.71},{"text":"And this elicit –-","start":1133.373,"stop":1133.521,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Insofar, you haven't come to the issues discussed by the Solicitor General.","start":1133.521,"stop":1138.14,"duration":4.62},{"text":"You're so far making a much broader argument as I understand it.","start":1138.14,"stop":1141.353,"duration":3.21},{"text":"You haven't come to Mr. Sisson yet?","start":1141.353,"stop":1143.317,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that is --","start":1143.317,"stop":1143.984,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You are telling us that Congress has no constitutional power to compel military service, at least in the absence of a declared war or a “national emergency” whatever that might be, and you say there is not now a national emergency, is that correct?","start":1143.984,"stop":1158.015,"duration":14.03}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, that's correct.","start":1158.015,"stop":1158.952,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You haven't come to Mr. Sisson, that his conscience or lack of it, is that correct?","start":1158.952,"stop":1162.393,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":1162.393,"stop":1163.478,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And you're seeking to sustain that justice below on another ground?","start":1163.478,"stop":1167.612,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think this Court is charged –-","start":1167.612,"stop":1169.964,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, --","start":1169.964,"stop":1170.576,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"-- yes.","start":1170.576,"stop":1170.783,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not -–","start":1170.783,"stop":1171.572,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1171.572,"stop":1171.963,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's accurately what you're doing?","start":1171.963,"stop":1173.39,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, it is.","start":1173.39,"stop":1175.385,"duration":1.99},{"text":"That is, there are a number of grounds which we assert.","start":1175.385,"stop":1179.57,"duration":4.18},{"text":"But I would, simply as the last comment to Mr. Justice Marshall's remark with respect to the difficulty of ascertaining, the meaning of conscience indicate that the draftsmen of the constitution had no problem with that.","start":1179.57,"stop":1197.963,"duration":18.39},{"text":"That is, I quote from Madison, “The freedom of the press and rights of conscience, those choices, privileges of the people are unguarded in the British Constitution”.","start":1197.963,"stop":1210.989,"duration":13.03},{"text":"He had no question, but that if there were no Bill of Rights, a man's right of conscience would nonetheless be protected.","start":1210.989,"stop":1216.86,"duration":5.87},{"text":"He didn't need a Bill of Rights.","start":1216.86,"stop":1218.158,"duration":1.3},{"text":"As a matter of fact, precisely the argument which the government now makes was the argument feared back then.","start":1218.158,"stop":1225.209,"duration":7.05},{"text":"That if you provided a Bill of Rights then, somebody would say, “Well, that's all you have.”","start":1225.209,"stop":1229.301,"duration":4.09},{"text":"Nothing else is protected, but the Ninth –-","start":1229.301,"stop":1229.441,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"In your grievance, did you allege the violation of the Bill of Rights?","start":1229.441,"stop":1235.819,"duration":6.38},{"text":"Sure you did, didn't you?","start":1235.819,"stop":1239.305,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I missed that, I'm sorry Your Honor.","start":1239.305,"stop":1241.179,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't the basis of your complaint that to adopt this man would violate his rights protected by the Bill of Right.","start":1241.179,"stop":1248.667,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1248.667,"stop":1249.441,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And now you're abandoning the Bill of Rights?","start":1249.441,"stop":1251.621,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we are not.","start":1251.621,"stop":1254.188,"duration":2.57},{"text":"We made several arguments and we maintain them all.","start":1254.188,"stop":1258.262,"duration":4.07},{"text":"That is, generally speaking, there are two arguments and the first argument is what power does Congress have under the clause which empowers it to raise and support armies, independently of the First Amendment.","start":1258.262,"stop":1273.446,"duration":15.18},{"text":"The second argument is whether that power is in some specifically –- a specific way limited by the first amendment.","start":1273.446,"stop":1281.022,"duration":7.58},{"text":"I am not addressing myself solely to the first question, forgetting about the Bill of Rights altogether, what power did the constitution confer upon Congress to raise and support armies?","start":1281.022,"stop":1292.967,"duration":11.95},{"text":"I do suggest respectfully that the history of the ratification of the constitution, of the dates at the constitutional convention simply do not blame themselves to any interpretation which would suggest that back then, it was thought that the federal government -– Congress could simply reach out and pluck people out for universal military service.","start":1292.967,"stop":1314.174,"duration":21.21},{"text":"That --","start":1314.174,"stop":1314.717,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you say we must read the Article 1 as meaning that the Congress has the power to raise and support armies in time of war but it's limited to that?","start":1314.717,"stop":1332.773,"duration":18.06}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"In time of national emergency, Your Honor.","start":1332.773,"stop":1334.645,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"In time of national emergency.","start":1334.645,"stop":1336.103,"duration":1.46},{"text":"Who's going to define the national emergency?","start":1336.103,"stop":1338.292,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well certainly, the Congress.","start":1338.292,"stop":1339.662,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress?","start":1339.662,"stop":1340.582,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"But Congress defines it for legislative purposes.","start":1340.582,"stop":1345.585,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what if the individual person being inducted did not agree that it was a national emergency?","start":1345.585,"stop":1352.635,"duration":7.05},{"text":"Could be escape service on the grounds of conscience?","start":1352.635,"stop":1355.792,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh no, no.","start":1355.792,"stop":1357.146,"duration":1.35},{"text":"If all he asserted, that's a perfect example to distinguish the two arguments.","start":1357.146,"stop":1361.227,"duration":4.08},{"text":"That is if –- as a matter of fact, that precise -– that sort of -– that sort of argument has a parallel with what happened during the war of 1812.","start":1361.227,"stop":1371.487,"duration":10.26},{"text":"That is, the president issued quotas the governors of various states, and the war was thought to be an unconstitutional war by many governors, particularly in New England.","start":1371.487,"stop":1382.449,"duration":10.96},{"text":"They simply refused to obey that order.","start":1382.449,"stop":1384.634,"duration":2.18},{"text":"And so we're not going to supply you militia.","start":1384.634,"stop":1388.445,"duration":3.81},{"text":"Now, furthermore, some of the militia –-","start":1388.445,"stop":1391.118,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Who was president then?","start":1391.118,"stop":1393.364,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"The president at that time, Your Honor, was Madison.","start":1393.364,"stop":1395.822,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"It was Madison?","start":1395.822,"stop":1396.81,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1396.81,"stop":1397.266,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The man whom you quoted a while ago?","start":1397.266,"stop":1399.102,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1399.102,"stop":1400.995,"duration":1.89},{"text":"The man who acted not under the power to raise and support armies, but rather under the militia clauses of Article 12 –- of Article 1, that is, the constitution provides a very, very plain scheme, provides for standing armies.","start":1400.995,"stop":1419.011,"duration":18.02},{"text":"Those were very, very, very much feared.","start":1419.011,"stop":1421.436,"duration":2.42},{"text":"In addition to standing armies for instance, the garrison, the frontier posts against the possibility of hostilities with the invasions.","start":1421.436,"stop":1429.889,"duration":8.45},{"text":"The constitution says well, if you have an insurrection or if you have an invasion, or if you have a problem with executing the laws, you can call out the state militias.","start":1429.889,"stop":1441.173,"duration":11.28},{"text":"The calling of the state militias meant something very specific.","start":1441.173,"stop":1443.826,"duration":2.65},{"text":"It meant you could only call them for three months, in any one year.","start":1443.826,"stop":1447.565,"duration":3.74},{"text":"You could only call them in rotation so that if you called them in once, you couldn't call them again until every other able bodied man, and his battalion had been called.","start":1447.565,"stop":1457.535,"duration":9.97},{"text":"Furthermore, you didn't call them for a specific length of time.","start":1457.535,"stop":1460.062,"duration":2.53},{"text":"You just called them out for that particular purpose.","start":1460.062,"stop":1462.785,"duration":2.72},{"text":"If you had a problem with the unions in one location, you call out the militia and they dealt with the unions there and then they went back home to their jobs, farmers, various other jobs which they are in.","start":1462.785,"stop":1474.8,"duration":12.01},{"text":"That was the scheme which the constitution provided.","start":1474.8,"stop":1479.999,"duration":5.2},{"text":"That is that's the way in which Congress was to deal with problems of national defense.","start":1479.999,"stop":1486.503,"duration":6.5},{"text":"We are conceding that in addition to what is clearly provided, in a clear case of national emergency where the national survival is at stake, it's perfectly clear that Congress must have the power to mobilize every resource.","start":1486.503,"stop":1503.85,"duration":17.35},{"text":"And certainly, that was contemplated, it is not denied.","start":1503.85,"stop":1507.815,"duration":3.97},{"text":"In the constitution therefore, we don't deny that it must exist by inference.","start":1507.815,"stop":1512.689,"duration":4.87},{"text":"But when we read the historical record without which that was simply cannot be read, that is you just can't raise and support armies literally unless you understand what they meant by a raise and support armies.","start":1512.689,"stop":1526.83,"duration":14.14},{"text":"Now, we deal with the historical argument at length in our brief.","start":1526.83,"stop":1531.131,"duration":4.3},{"text":"I think we demonstrate very clearly that the power to conscript was feared.","start":1531.131,"stop":1536.548,"duration":5.42},{"text":"It was not even used in the revolutionary war except in very limited circumstances.","start":1536.548,"stop":1543.746,"duration":7.2},{"text":"At the height –- at the height of the idealism which motivated the men who were fighting for their freedom of this country.","start":1543.746,"stop":1551.354,"duration":7.61}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"If Congress enacted a resolution declaring the situation in Vietnam, a national emergency, would you -– would you then dismiss your appeal?","start":1551.354,"stop":1563.784,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"We would have a very, very different case, Your Honor, but that is precisely what we have in mind.","start":1563.784,"stop":1568.585,"duration":4.8},{"text":"That is, the declaration of war is –-","start":1568.585,"stop":1571.449,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I did not say a declaration of war.","start":1571.449,"stop":1572.72,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, Your Honor, but that would be one very clear example of a declaration of a national emergency.","start":1572.72,"stop":1579.339,"duration":6.62},{"text":"It's one thing to say we really need to do this.","start":1579.339,"stop":1582.403,"duration":3.06},{"text":"It's quite another matter to enact the statute which is designed not simply to meet with national emergencies but to deal with peace time conditions and to apply it in peace time rather than limiting its application to war time conditions, or national emergency conditions.","start":1582.403,"stop":1601.61,"duration":19.21},{"text":"But it just –- it just was beyond anything that any of advancement or any of the people at the time that the constitution was adopted that this federal government, this body of people could simply reach out and conscript people.","start":1601.61,"stop":1618.844,"duration":17.23},{"text":"If they can do it now, why couldn't they have done it back then?","start":1618.844,"stop":1621.867,"duration":3.02},{"text":"Why couldn't they simply conscript one million men?","start":1621.867,"stop":1624.782,"duration":2.91},{"text":"We're going to have a standing army of one million men.","start":1624.782,"stop":1626.788,"duration":2.01},{"text":"Furthermore, we're going to induct them, we're going to conscript them for ten years because we think we ought to have a very strong army.","start":1626.788,"stop":1633.744,"duration":6.96},{"text":"Yet it just is inconceivable that that power was granted.","start":1633.744,"stop":1637.921,"duration":4.18},{"text":"It just was not granted.","start":1637.921,"stop":1639.24,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is your central argument against the standing army on the constitutional ground?","start":1639.24,"stop":1644.563,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Not against the standing army, Your Honor.","start":1644.563,"stop":1646.397,"duration":1.83},{"text":"The standing army composed of volunteers is precisely –-","start":1646.397,"stop":1649.388,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I know, but again the conscripting?","start":1649.388,"stop":1651.551,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, absolutely, Your Honor.","start":1651.551,"stop":1653.403,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"A standing army?","start":1653.403,"stop":1655.341,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Of conscripts, yes, Your Honor.","start":1655.341,"stop":1657.61,"duration":2.27},{"text":"During the first 150 years of the history of this country, that's precisely what Congress did continuously.","start":1657.61,"stop":1664.313,"duration":6.7},{"text":"It resorted to volunteers, not for various reasons of social policy.","start":1664.313,"stop":1669.322,"duration":5.01},{"text":"Congress has decided.","start":1669.322,"stop":1670.115,"duration":0.79},{"text":"Well, we don't like that scheme.","start":1670.115,"stop":1672.163,"duration":2.05},{"text":"That is, if what –-","start":1672.163,"stop":1673.038,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What you are challenging as I understand is in the Court's hand, you first told me that there could be a conscript and I may -- could be used into time of peace was rather than war?","start":1673.038,"stop":1686.422,"duration":13.38}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor, that's correct.","start":1686.422,"stop":1688.708,"duration":2.29},{"text":"We concede there is power to conscript when you have a genuine national emergency.","start":1688.708,"stop":1693.162,"duration":4.45},{"text":"There just was no power to which was conferred.","start":1693.162,"stop":1695.692,"duration":2.53},{"text":"To raise a standing army –-","start":1695.692,"stop":1697.028,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"To determine whether there was a national emergency?","start":1697.028,"stop":1700.476,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1700.476,"stop":1701.334,"duration":0.86},{"text":"You can determine it in many, many ways.","start":1701.334,"stop":1703.438,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But who would decide it finally?","start":1703.438,"stop":1706.608,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"The final arbitrar with respect to the limits of power which Congress has.","start":1706.608,"stop":1714.02,"duration":7.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Who would decide it?","start":1714.02,"stop":1715.212,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Always this Court, that is.","start":1715.212,"stop":1716.658,"duration":1.45},{"text":"I don't think it's –-","start":1716.658,"stop":1717.153,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"This Court?","start":1717.153,"stop":1718.489,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I think ultimately, this Court must decide any argument that Congress has exceeded the limits of its power.","start":1718.489,"stop":1727.183,"duration":8.69},{"text":"But certainly, action taken by congress, unequivocal action declaring the existence of an emergency would be very persuasive, not necessarily conclusive but I think we –- we would have very, very little hope of prevailing if Congress had said well, we've got a national emergency and we absolutely need to conscript men.","start":1727.183,"stop":1747.302,"duration":20.12},{"text":"But we don't have that situation at all.","start":1747.302,"stop":1749.483,"duration":2.18},{"text":"For the last six years, there've been studies upon studies as to whether volunteer army was feasible, clearly testified time and time again both by government persons who opposed a no-volunteer army as well as by men who preferred the volunteer army that it is feasible.","start":1749.483,"stop":1766.866,"duration":17.38},{"text":"I mean, manpower is available.","start":1766.866,"stop":1769.612,"duration":2.75},{"text":"It just costs money.","start":1769.612,"stop":1771.402,"duration":1.79},{"text":"But that's the way in which a standing army has been raised for 150 years.","start":1771.402,"stop":1778.164,"duration":6.76},{"text":"And it was never suggested that Congress could simply say, “Well, we don't think we ought to be spending money this way.","start":1778.164,"stop":1784.044,"duration":5.88},{"text":"We're not going to do it.","start":1784.044,"stop":1785.415,"duration":1.37},{"text":"We'll save the little money.","start":1785.415,"stop":1786.595,"duration":1.18},{"text":"Furthermore, we think it's democratic.","start":1786.595,"stop":1789.058,"duration":2.46},{"text":"We don't a mercenary army.”","start":1789.058,"stop":1791.524,"duration":2.47},{"text":"Maybe Congress does think that there are valid reasons for conscripting men instead of simply having volunteers to mend this standing army in peace time.","start":1791.524,"stop":1803.983,"duration":12.46},{"text":"But that doesn't change the power that Congress -– that was delegated to Congress at the time the constitution was adopted.","start":1803.983,"stop":1810.585,"duration":6.6}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Did England have a standing army at the time this country was colonized?","start":1810.585,"stop":1815.588,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Standing armies were recognized, Your Honor, but never of conscripts.","start":1815.588,"stop":1820.548,"duration":4.96},{"text":"Conscription for a standing army as a historical fact did not even occur until after the constitution –-","start":1820.548,"stop":1828.164,"duration":7.62}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they have a standing army or did they have an army which was called in the service year to year or two years –- two years?","start":1828.164,"stop":1837.605,"duration":9.44}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it was of limited duration.","start":1837.605,"stop":1840.125,"duration":2.52},{"text":"That is, my recollection is that the standing army in England was –- well, for a limited period of time.","start":1840.125,"stop":1853.826,"duration":13.7},{"text":"I don't remember exactly, Your Honor.","start":1853.826,"stop":1855.533,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"With what?","start":1855.533,"stop":1856.052,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't remember exactly, but it was for a limited period of time.","start":1856.052,"stop":1859.342,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1859.342,"stop":1860.438,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"But it was -– it was not composed of conscripts.","start":1860.438,"stop":1863.805,"duration":3.37},{"text":"It was volunteers entirely, except -– except for beggars.","start":1863.805,"stop":1868.779,"duration":4.97},{"text":"That is, beggars could be impressed but that was as a form of punishment.","start":1868.779,"stop":1878.426,"duration":9.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, might that have been the reason they put in to the constitution or Congress to raise armies?","start":1878.426,"stop":1885.408,"duration":6.98}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think Your Honor, the historical record is clear that the power to raise and support armies is included because a standing army as feared as it was, and it was very, very much feared because the fear was that Congress would use the standing army to eliminate the power of the states and to oppress the individual citizens in the states.","start":1885.408,"stop":1907.113,"duration":21.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In favor to a militia?","start":1907.113,"stop":1909.495,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh absolutely!","start":1909.495,"stop":1911.265,"duration":1.77},{"text":"There are at least five separate preferences to militia.","start":1911.265,"stop":1914.966,"duration":3.7},{"text":"That is, you have at least three clauses in Article 1 which deal expressly with militia.","start":1914.966,"stop":1922.099,"duration":7.13},{"text":"And again, militia were to be called and specified circumstance only while the emergency lasted.","start":1922.099,"stop":1930.188,"duration":8.09},{"text":"In the Second Amendment for instance, the Second Amendment provides that individual citizens had the right to keep and bear arms because you need a strong militia so that the state can defend itself.","start":1930.188,"stop":1941.019,"duration":10.83},{"text":"The argument that a standing army was all right was based repeatedly on the argument that Congress could never amass a standing army of such power that it could overcome the power of the states because they had the militia and the militia were very, very numerous.","start":1941.019,"stop":1957.882,"duration":16.86}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"As I recall it or my memory maybe entirely wrong.","start":1957.882,"stop":1962.037,"duration":4.15},{"text":"Those who insisted on having nothing but a militia, state militia, were defeated in the constitutional convention and it was provided that the Congress agrees on?","start":1962.037,"stop":1978.125,"duration":16.09}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"That's absolutely correct, Your Honor, but it's important to bear in mind that the concept of a standing army was agreed to in a very, very limited way that is precisely the opposition which you are noted, that people will say, “Well, you don't need a standing army, we've got our state militia.”","start":1978.125,"stop":1999.122,"duration":21},{"text":"The argument was well, are you going to take farmers and post them on garrison posts on the frontiers to combat the unions?","start":1999.122,"stop":2006.759,"duration":7.64},{"text":"We need an army, a standing army.","start":2006.759,"stop":2008.592,"duration":1.83},{"text":"Now, what did that mean?","start":2008.592,"stop":2010.304,"duration":1.71},{"text":"The very first Congress enacted a bill.","start":2010.304,"stop":2012.438,"duration":2.13},{"text":"I had as a matter of fact, starting by 1789, 1790, 1791, 1792, 1793, 1794, 1795, there are separate bills, numerous, dealing with the army, the standing army, as well as with militia but in quite separate ways.","start":2012.438,"stop":2026.969,"duration":14.53},{"text":"And the standing army that was provided consisted of I think 1,200 men, meant to deal very expressly with the problem of the frontiers.","start":2026.969,"stop":2035.976,"duration":9.01}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"May I remind you, Mr. Flym, you are now using your rebuttal time.","start":2035.976,"stop":2039.855,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, Your Honor, I have no rebuttal.","start":2039.855,"stop":2041.78,"duration":1.92},{"text":"I think –-","start":2041.78,"stop":2043.069,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me, as I've forgotten on our start-– you started to do -– you were on yesterday, yes, yes, excuse me.","start":2043.069,"stop":2049.478,"duration":6.41},{"text":"Already have.","start":2049.478,"stop":2049.538,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Forgive me, Your Honor.","start":2049.538,"stop":2051.34,"duration":1.8},{"text":"In any event, I really don't think I should spend more time on this argument.","start":2051.34,"stop":2058.219,"duration":6.88},{"text":"I would like to mention another separate argument.","start":2058.219,"stop":2061.498,"duration":3.28},{"text":"That is, I simply mentioned that in passing.","start":2061.498,"stop":2064.443,"duration":2.95},{"text":"That is that if a non-volunteer army is feasible, Congress just can't pick and choose ways of raising men and say, “Well, we're not going to spend the money so that we'll have this money available for the project.”","start":2064.443,"stop":2080.922,"duration":16.48},{"text":"That is, if they can raise volunteers, they're required to raise volunteers for the standing army.","start":2080.922,"stop":2086.426,"duration":5.5},{"text":"That was the original concept.","start":2086.426,"stop":2088.344,"duration":1.92},{"text":"As a matter of fact, the concept -– the word “raise armies” is used repeatedly by the first congress, by the early Congresses, and they specified that they mean volunteers and the deal with militia entirely separately.","start":2088.344,"stop":2102.048,"duration":13.7},{"text":"As a matter of fact in one case, they increased the size of the authorized army I think to 5,000 men, and they said, “But we want to make it clear that as soon as the emergency is over, that army is to be disbanded.","start":2102.048,"stop":2114.725,"duration":12.68},{"text":"We don't want it around.","start":2114.725,"stop":2115.7,"duration":0.97},{"text":"We want that number reduced to 1,500.”","start":2115.7,"stop":2118.889,"duration":3.19},{"text":"And so now, I won't even touch on the argument that the power of Congress is further limited so that it can't raise an army for an illegal war.","start":2118.889,"stop":2132.652,"duration":13.76},{"text":"Now, that's dealt within our brief.","start":2132.652,"stop":2135.519,"duration":2.87},{"text":"I think it's much too complex to even begin at this point.","start":2135.519,"stop":2138.568,"duration":3.05},{"text":"I would, if I may, like to turn for the remaining time to the solicitor's argument with respect to the establishment issue, as well as the free exercise issue.","start":2138.568,"stop":2152.459,"duration":13.89},{"text":"Incidentally, Mr. Justice Marshall, I checked in to various authorities on the question bearing on whether we have an rest of judgment decision more in a -– well, another authority, I'm very bad on issues, right, it simply don't communicate if there's anything to be done after you grant the motion of rest of judgment, you grant it and that's it.","start":2152.459,"stop":2179.824,"duration":27.37},{"text":"And I checked the records in this Court in the cases of Bramblett as well as the case of Green, they are cited at page 15 of our brief, and I looked at the order entered by the lower courts in those cases and that's all they say, motion to rest of judgment granted.","start":2179.824,"stop":2199.577,"duration":19.75},{"text":"I found no indication that there's anything else which anyone else thought needed to be done.","start":2199.577,"stop":2204.798,"duration":5.22},{"text":"On the establishment question simply indicate that on the basis of the Solicitor General's argument, it's perfectly clear that the act tends to establish pacifist religions.","start":2204.798,"stop":2219.092,"duration":14.29},{"text":"That's what the Act has intended -– well, it isn't intended to establish them but it is intended to protect members of pacifist religions.","start":2219.092,"stop":2228.768,"duration":9.68},{"text":"Now, the Solicitor General says, “That's alright, that's alright because religion doesn't mean what we say it means within the First Amendment,” and that's because the First Amendment somehow can't be used in this way to limit the power of Congress to raise and support armies.","start":2228.768,"stop":2246.313,"duration":17.55},{"text":"I think that -– that logically it falls from everything I've said up to now, that that just isn't true.","start":2246.313,"stop":2252.812,"duration":6.5},{"text":"Historically, that is completely inaccurate.","start":2252.812,"stop":2256.776,"duration":3.96},{"text":"Now, on the free exercise of religion argument, there's an important misconception that must be dealt with.","start":2256.776,"stop":2270.551,"duration":13.78},{"text":"We're not dealing here with a non-religious objector, I mentioned that yesterday.","start":2270.551,"stop":2277.875,"duration":7.32},{"text":"This man is a non-religious in the statutory sense, conscientious objector.","start":2277.875,"stop":2283.694,"duration":5.82},{"text":"Now, the question is whether he's –-","start":2283.694,"stop":2286.028,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But he's a non -– non-religious, conscientious, selective objector?","start":2286.028,"stop":2291.147,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2291.147,"stop":2291.646,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":2291.646,"stop":2291.688,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Selective objector.","start":2291.688,"stop":2293.329,"duration":1.64},{"text":"Now, that's correct Your Honor.","start":2293.329,"stop":2295.935,"duration":2.61},{"text":"Now, the question is not whether he can pick and choose his war but whether religions, including established religions, recognize the concept of just war.","start":2295.935,"stop":2313.382,"duration":17.45},{"text":"I don't think there's any question about the fact that today at least, Protestant, Catholic, Jewish organizations, the Vatican Council, all have made it perfectly plain that they think that there are differences between wars.","start":2313.382,"stop":2331.266,"duration":17.88},{"text":"Some wars are okay and some aren't.","start":2331.266,"stop":2334.648,"duration":3.38},{"text":"That is, as religious organizations, it just doesn't seem to me that the argument can be made that if a man objects to a particular war, he necessarily has a “political” objection as opposed to a religious objection.","start":2334.648,"stop":2349.024,"duration":14.38},{"text":"That just doesn't square with the facts.","start":2349.024,"stop":2352.287,"duration":3.26},{"text":"Again, I think that whether you reach this conclusion or not depends on your concept of the power of Congress to raise and support armies.","start":2352.287,"stop":2363.774,"duration":11.49},{"text":"If you conceive of it as being completely uncontrollable, then it might make sense to apply much more restrictive notion of what is meant by religion in the First Amendment insofar as it relates to the power of Congress to raise and support armies.","start":2363.774,"stop":2381.245,"duration":17.47},{"text":"But I just don't think there's any support, any historical support with the view that Congress in 1789 could simply reach out and say, “I'm going to take you.","start":2381.245,"stop":2393.443,"duration":12.2},{"text":"I know its peace time.","start":2393.443,"stop":2394.459,"duration":1.02},{"text":"I know we don't have any wars, but we've got -– we've got to have a strong army.” Just absolutely no support for that view.","start":2394.459,"stop":2402.677,"duration":8.22},{"text":"If there are no questions, I'll submit.","start":2402.677,"stop":2405.843,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Flym.","start":2405.843,"stop":2407.445,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"John G. S. Flym","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":2407.445,"stop":2414.731,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Solicitor General?","start":2414.731,"stop":2415.07,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":2415.07,"stop":2417.935,"duration":2.86},{"text":"First, with respect to the jurisdictional question, Mr. Justice Harlan asked me yesterday about a statute which has been opposed in Congress.","start":2417.935,"stop":2431.04,"duration":13.11},{"text":"It is referred to in a footnote on pages 15 and particularly on page 16 of our brief where there is a reference to the congressional record.","start":2431.04,"stop":2444.312,"duration":13.27},{"text":"I have obtained a Xerox copy of that page with the congressional record and also a copy of the bill, and I will lodge it with the clerk if that is helpful to the Court.","start":2444.312,"stop":2458.084,"duration":13.77},{"text":"The proposed statute is simple and I think clear.","start":2458.084,"stop":2462.731,"duration":4.65},{"text":"It provides –- it would supersede the first seven paragraphs of the present Section 3731 and would substitute “In a criminal case, an appeal by the United States shall lie to a Court of Appeals from a judgment or order of a District Court dismissing an indictment or information, or terminating a prosecution in favor of a defendant as to any one or more counts, except that no appeal shall lie from a judgment of acquittal, provided however that when the judgment or order is based solely on a determination of the invalidity of an Act of congress, the appeal shall lie directly to the Supreme Court.”","start":2462.731,"stop":2510.007,"duration":47.28},{"text":"The direct appeal would only be in the case of the invalidity and not the construction –-","start":2510.007,"stop":2515.931,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you have any questions, Mr. Solicitor General, about this -– the ability of this Court, the power of this Court to transfer to a Court of Appeals in this case?","start":2515.931,"stop":2526.188,"duration":10.26}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"There would be no such provision under this –- yes, I suspect there would be.","start":2526.188,"stop":2531.503,"duration":5.32},{"text":"The provision for transfer would still –-","start":2531.503,"stop":2534.035,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think be applicable to this type?","start":2534.035,"stop":2535.345,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Would still stay in because this simply is a substitute for the first seven paragraphs and the transfer provisions are in the subsequent paragraphs –-","start":2535.345,"stop":2546.184,"duration":10.84}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Under existing law, we could view that?","start":2546.184,"stop":2548.2,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"So that if this Court concluded that no question of the constitutionality of a statute was involved, it could transfer it to a Court of Appeals.","start":2548.2,"stop":2560.409,"duration":12.21},{"text":"Now in addition --","start":2560.409,"stop":2561.218,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"With the present bill, Mr. Solicitor General, or the present statute of the –-","start":2561.218,"stop":2565.201,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"The present statute provides for transfer both ways, from the Court of Appeals to the -– and we have recently filed a motion for a transfer of a case from this stage to a Court of Appeals, which I regretted having to file, but we find it very baffling to tell in some cases where the appeal should lie.","start":2565.201,"stop":2586.986,"duration":21.78},{"text":"I may say that I have in addition prepared Xerox copies of all of the pages of the congressional record back in 1909 where the Criminal Appeals Act was discussed, and I will lodge that, too, with the Court because it might be convenient in examining that.","start":2586.986,"stop":2609.901,"duration":22.91},{"text":"I will lodge that with the clerk because it might be convenient in examining the matter.","start":2609.901,"stop":2614.319,"duration":4.42}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Solicitor, go back to that statute for a moment.","start":2614.319,"stop":2620.309,"duration":5.99},{"text":"As you read it, as you see it, the direct appeal to this Court did not foreclose the application of the transfer statute and therefore, the direct appeal is I take it simply to provide expedition in a proper case where important interests were involved.","start":2620.309,"stop":2648.158,"duration":27.85},{"text":"Is that it?","start":2648.158,"stop":2648.781,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, where the constitutionality of the Act of Congress is involved, that's the only question.","start":2648.781,"stop":2654.735,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But to –- I am speaking -– addressing myself just to the reasons, the congressional reasons that you see for the direct appeal was because I am would be –- it might well be of the essence in those cases?","start":2654.735,"stop":2666.821,"duration":12.09}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the department felt and it has been the practice of Congress elsewhere that when an Act of Congress is held unconstitutional, that is an important question which ought to come to this Court.","start":2666.821,"stop":2682.149,"duration":15.33}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"But it might not always involve a great issue of time necessarily, would it?","start":2682.149,"stop":2687.812,"duration":5.66}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"It might not be essentially a great issue, but holding an Act of Congress unconstitutional is a great issue.","start":2687.812,"stop":2695.662,"duration":7.85}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Without regard to the time factors involved?","start":2695.662,"stop":2698.852,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Without regard to the time factors involved, I believe.","start":2698.852,"stop":2703.185,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you, Mr. Solicitor General, suppose a trial judge makes some findings of fact as a basis for his arrest or his order arresting judgment, facts which were stipulated to or anything else.","start":2703.185,"stop":2724.479,"duration":21.29},{"text":"And suppose that the –- these weren't evident on the face of the indictment and so on and that this couldn't properly be called an arrest of judgment, what happens then in terms of appeal?","start":2724.479,"stop":2739.383,"duration":14.9},{"text":"I suppose it wouldn't and I assume it isn't the plea in bar or it isn't –-","start":2739.383,"stop":2743.459,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"If it --","start":2743.459,"stop":2744.957,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly wouldn't be just a motion –- just a dismissal of the indictment since he's made factual findings.","start":2744.957,"stop":2750.438,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"If it can't be called a motion in arrest of judgment, then the only basis for appeal would be to call it a motion in bar where the statutes expressly says when the defendant has not been put in jeopardy, whether it would or would not be a motion of bar is a point upon which members of the Court have been in disagreement.","start":2750.438,"stop":2775.434,"duration":25}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Your position is that he has been placed in jeopardy in this case?","start":2775.434,"stop":2778.848,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Our position is that he has been placed in jeopardy.","start":2778.848,"stop":2781.029,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So you wouldn't think an appeal would lie into that sense?","start":2781.029,"stop":2783.215,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, so you would then have to come under from a decision or judgment setting aside or dismissing any indictment or information, or any count thereof, where it is based on the invalidity or construction of the statute.","start":2783.215,"stop":2797.332,"duration":14.12}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Under that -– does the same sort of fact finding vitiate an appeal under that provision like it does in the arrest of judgment?","start":2797.332,"stop":2806.413,"duration":9.08}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, rightly or wrongly, we don't get to that because we construe that in the light of the legislative history as also involving the question whether the defendant has been put in jeopardy.","start":2806.413,"stop":2820.842,"duration":14.43},{"text":"And if the defendant has been put in jeopardy, we not only so construe it but there's a long practice within the Department of Justice at least accepted by this Court to the same effect.","start":2820.842,"stop":2837.574,"duration":16.73},{"text":"Now, if your findings of fact were held, were made before the empanelling of the jury, for example, if the Court said, “I am greatly troubled by the validity of the statute in this case, but I'm not sure about the facts and can we have a factual hearing which will have evidence,” and he then finds facts from which he concludes that the statute is unconstitutional, no jury ever having been in panel, then I would suppose that the first clause would apply.","start":2837.574,"stop":2868.84,"duration":31.27}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But if it –- but if we disagreed with the government here and said that there were fact finding and there was a species of fact finding here in this case which removed it from the arrest of judgment category, then there just wouldn't be an appeal anywhere?","start":2868.84,"stop":2886.205,"duration":17.36}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Then we are unable to find a basis for jurisdiction of this Court on appeal.","start":2886.205,"stop":2893.738,"duration":7.53},{"text":"If this Court can find it, we would of course accept –-","start":2893.738,"stop":2896.551,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if we could not, could it be transferred to the Court of Appeals?","start":2896.551,"stop":2901.627,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"I think not, Mr. Justice.","start":2901.627,"stop":2903.57,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, there's no appeal anywhere?","start":2903.57,"stop":2905.137,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"There would be no appeal anywhere.","start":2905.137,"stop":2906.744,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what do you think the case should -- should happen to the case and that's the presumption?","start":2906.744,"stop":2915.333,"duration":8.59}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court concludes that it has no jurisdiction, the sole basis of the appeal being with respect to the Court's construction and determination of the constitutionality of the Act of Congress, then I think the Court should dismiss the appeal.","start":2915.333,"stop":2931.947,"duration":16.61}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What posture does that leaves the --","start":2931.947,"stop":2933.859,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"That leaves the decision in arrest of judgment outstanding, and that means that while that is outstanding and no one can, neither this Court nor the Court of Appeals can upset it, that it would not be possible to proceed further on the verdict of the jury.","start":2933.859,"stop":2952.93,"duration":19.07}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Would it be possible to vacate the proceeding below, send them back to the District Court and they can do what they think should be done by way of appellate jurisdiction --","start":2952.93,"stop":2965.173,"duration":12.24}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, with respect, I think not.","start":2965.173,"stop":2969.201,"duration":4.03},{"text":"If this Court has no jurisdiction, it has no jurisdiction.","start":2969.201,"stop":2972.93,"duration":3.73}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Then you would be carving out, Mr. Solicitor General.","start":2972.93,"stop":2976.576,"duration":3.65},{"text":"You would not be, but the consequence of your position would be that there would be carved out a final decision of a District Judge holding an Act of Congress unconstitutional which is un-reviewable by anyone?","start":2976.576,"stop":2993.418,"duration":16.84}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice -- Mr. Chief Justice, that was what the law undoubtedly was in all respects until 1909 and all that we can say is that Congress in its great care with respect to the double jeopardy simply has not yet made available an appeal in that case.","start":2993.418,"stop":3013.966,"duration":20.55},{"text":"We are trying to persuade the Congress to take care of the problem and I hope we can.","start":3013.966,"stop":3020.023,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose, Mr. Solicitor General however if this Court and some other case, unrelated case or some other case should express its views, and if those views were inconsistent with the views reached by Judge Wyzanski in this case, there would be nothing to prevent the government from going to the District Court and asking -– making a motion for the modification for the arrest of judgment, would there?","start":3020.023,"stop":3048.951,"duration":28.93}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -– we'll keep in mind, Mr. Justice.","start":3048.951,"stop":3051.732,"duration":2.78},{"text":"I don't –- I don't -– whether that would be good policy or not, I don't know.","start":3051.732,"stop":3058.441,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would you Mr. Solicitor, would you be up against at least the problem whether even that would constitute a violation of double jeopardy?","start":3058.441,"stop":3066.691,"duration":8.25}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"There of course would be a problem but offhand, it seems to me it is answerable.","start":3066.691,"stop":3072.844,"duration":6.15},{"text":"For example, suppose there had been a petition for rehearing filed in -– before Judge Wyzanski the next day, one reason I'm hesitant is I'm not familiar with what the rule provisions are as to the time and there might come a time when it would be said that that was final and amounted to an acquittal.","start":3072.844,"stop":3090.813,"duration":17.97},{"text":"It was not informed an acquittal.","start":3090.813,"stop":3093.005,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you -- we certainly have enough jurisdictions to say what whether we have to?","start":3093.005,"stop":3097.468,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice.","start":3097.468,"stop":3098.626,"duration":1.16},{"text":"The Court has decided that it has jurisdiction to decide whether it has –-","start":3098.626,"stop":3102.62,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not according to it, assuming that much jurisdiction at least and assuming on the underlying question, the conclusion is there is no direct review of the case, is that limited jurisdiction it would have.","start":3102.62,"stop":3115.88,"duration":13.26},{"text":"It was from our -- number 2106, as in sending this back to the District Court?","start":3115.88,"stop":3119.952,"duration":4.07},{"text":"Let's just assume that our --","start":3119.952,"stop":3125.014,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"Erwin N. Griswold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Justice, I would think that if you concluded that you had no jurisdiction, the case had never left the District Court, and you would not have power to send it back with any directions or instructions of any kind.","start":3125.014,"stop":3138.936,"duration":13.92},{"text":"There is a suggestion here in the argument today that Sisson's objection was not a selective one.","start":3138.936,"stop":3148.433,"duration":9.5},{"text":"On that, I would simply refer to page 151 of the appendix, Sisson's testimony which the government accepts as part of the agreed statement of facts here, “I refused induction because I believe the war in Vietnam, that is the United States war making in Vietnam, to be wrong.”","start":3148.433,"stop":3170.246,"duration":21.81},{"text":"He then went on to say, “That therefore, I felt that by accepting induction that even though I might not be sent to Vietnam, I would be consenting to the government's waging a war in Vietnam and I believe that my duty not to consent with that action because I did not consent in my own mind.”","start":3170.246,"stop":3190.782,"duration":20.54},{"text":"With respect to the power of Congress to impose a peace time military service, I was fortunate enough to go off in a country which did not have conscription, and I suppose I regarded that as something which would last for all time.","start":3190.782,"stop":3209.858,"duration":19.08},{"text":"It would be fine if we could get to that situation.","start":3209.858,"stop":3214.716,"duration":4.86},{"text":"I would point out though that Congress enacted the modern conscription laws in 1940, which was technically a time of peace, actually a time of peace in this country.","start":3214.716,"stop":3227.745,"duration":13.03},{"text":"That the problem of reenacting that statute in 1941 also came up in a time of peace in this country, and it would be rather surprising if it should now be held that Congress had no power to pass those statutes.","start":3227.745,"stop":3248.826,"duration":21.08},{"text":"Let me conclude by simply saying that our professional historian friends are rather skeptical of lawyer's history.","start":3248.826,"stop":3264.827,"duration":16},{"text":"They refer to it as law office history and regarded as –- to use an appropriate word, as highly selective. C.V. Wedgwood, the noted historian, wrote one time, “We know the end before we consider the beginning and we can never wholly recapture what it was to know the beginning only.”","start":3264.827,"stop":3294.576,"duration":29.75},{"text":"And our submission here is that the Court should not find in history something that surely was not there.","start":3294.576,"stop":3303.654,"duration":9.08},{"text":"Our predecessors were sensitive to the First Amendment, but the founders accepted the exemption from military service for members of the peace churches without any question, and this was accepted explicitly in the Acts of Congress for 130 years right through the First World War.","start":3303.654,"stop":3328.763,"duration":25.11},{"text":"It would be odd indeed if the invalidity of this unbroken practice was now discovered for the first time a 180 years after the adoption of the Bill of Rights.","start":3328.763,"stop":3342.069,"duration":13.31}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Solicitor General for your submission.","start":3342.069,"stop":3345.168,"duration":3.1},{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Flym.","start":3345.168,"stop":3346.472,"duration":1.3},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3346.472,"stop":3349.482,"duration":3.01}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Jan  20 - 21, 1970","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"305","citation":"399 US 267 (1970)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/399/267","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 29, 1970"}